{"title_page": "Secretary of State of Arkansas", "text_new": "{{short description|Cabinet officer in the government of the U.S. state of Arkansas}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Secretary of State\n|body            = Arkansas\n|insignia        = Seal of Arkansas.svg\n|insigniasize    = 110px\n|insigniacaption = [[Great Seal of Arkansas|State seal]]\n|image           = \n|incumbent       = [[John Thurston (politician)|John Thurston]]\n|incumbentsince  = January 15, 2019\n|style           =\n|appointer       =\n|termlength      = 4 years\n|formation       = [[Constitution of Arkansas|Arkansas Constitution]]<br />1836, 1868 and 1874\n|succession      =\n|inaugural       = Robert A. Watkins<br />1836\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.sos.arkansas.gov/}}\n|salary          = $54,305<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Arkansas_state_government_salary |title=Arkansas state government salary |publisher=Ballotpedia |access-date=February 4, 2018 }}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Secretary of State of Arkansas''' is one of the elected constitutional officers of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Arkansas]].\n\nThe current Secretary of State is the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[John Thurston (politician)|John Thurston]], former [[Arkansas Land Commissioner]] from [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]] in central Arkansas.\n\n==Organization==\nThe Secretary of State's Office is composed of seven divisions:\n\n*The Building & Grounds Division maintains the [[Arkansas State Capitol]] and its surrounding grounds and gardens.\n*The Business & Commercial Services Division is responsible for filing [[lien]]s pursuant to the [[Uniform Commercial Code]], registering [[business entities]] and [[trademark]]s, collecting the state [[franchise tax]], and licensing [[Notary public|notaries public]].\n*The Communications & Education Division provides public education about [[civics]] and the [[History of Arkansas]], and produces various state publications.\n*The Elections Division administers elections, regulates [[campaign finance]] and [[lobbying]], and ensures compliance with state and federal [[election law]]s.\n*The Fiscal Office deals with the internal financial, logistical, and personnel matters of the Office of the Secretary of State.  They also distribute the [[Flag of Arkansas|Arkansas]] and [[Flag of the United States|United States flag]].\n*The Secretary also runs the State Capitol Gift Shop.\n*The State Capitol Police provide security for the State Capitol building and police services for the Capitol Complex.\n\n==Other duties==\nThe Secretary of State also publishes the state's [[Administrative law|administrative regulations]] and the state [[gazette]], the ''Arkansas Register''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sos.arkansas.gov/rules-regulations |publisher=Arkansas Secretary of State |title=Rules & Regulations |access-date=May 10, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Officeholders==\n[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] were elected exclusively to the office of Secretary of State from the later [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction era]] until the retirement of [[Charlie Daniels (politician)|Charlie Daniels]] to run for State Auditor in 2010, when the first modern-day Republican to hold the office, Mark Martin, was elected. Secretaries of state during the statehood of Arkansas include:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?search=1&entryID=5723 |title=Office of Secretary of State |website=The Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture |access-date=February 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* [[Robert A. Watkins]] (D) 1836\u20131840\n* [[D. B. Greer]] 1840\u20131842\n* [[John Winfrey]] (D) 1842\n* [[D. B. Greer]] (D) 1842\u20131859\n* [[Alexander Boileau]] (D) 1859\u20131860\n* [[S. W. Weaver]] (D) 1860\n* [[John I. Stirman]] (D/Confederate) 1860\u20131862\n* [[O. H. Oates]] (Confederate) 1862\u20131864\n* [[Robert J. T. White]] (R) 1864\u20131871\n* [[James M. Johnson (Arkansas)|James M. Johnson]] (R) 1871\u20131874\n* [[Benton B. Beavers]] (D) 1874\u20131879\n* [[Jacob Frolich]] (D) 1879\u20131885\n* [[Elias B. Moore]] (D) 1885\u20131889\n* [[B. B. Chism]] (D) 1889\u20131893\n* [[H. B. Armistead]] (D) 1893\u20131897\n* [[Alexander C. Hull]] (D) 1897\u20131901\n* [[J. W. Crockett]] (D) 1901\u20131905\n* [[O. C. Ludwig]] (D) 1905\u20131911\n* [[Earle W. Hodges]] (D) 1911\u20131917\n* [[Tom J. Terral]] (D) 1917\u20131921\n* [[Ira C. Hopper]] (D) 1921\u20131925\n* [[Jim B. Higgins]] (D) 1925\u20131931\n* [[Ed F. McDonald]] (D) 1931\u20131937\n* [[Claris Hall|C. G. \"Crip\" Hall]] (D) 1937\u20131961\n* [[Nancy Hall|Nancy J. Hall]] (D) 1961\u20131963\n* [[Kelly Bryant (politician)|Kelly Bryant]] (D) 1963\u20131975\n* [[George O. Jernigan Jr.]] (D) 1975\u20131977\n* [[Winston Bryant]] (D) 1977\u20131979\n* [[Paul Riviere (politician)|Paul Riviere]] (D) 1979\u20131985\n* [[William J. \"Bill\" McCuen]] (D) 1985\u20131995\n* [[Sharon M. Priest]] (D) 1995\u20132003\n* [[Charlie Daniels (politician)|Charlie Daniels]] (D) 2003\u20132011\n* [[Mark Martin (Arkansas politician)|Mark Martin]] (R) 2011\u20132019\n* [[John Thurston (politician)|John Thurston]] (R) 2019\u2013present\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of company registers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.sos.arkansas.gov/ Official homepage of the Arkansas Secretary of State]\n\n{{U.S. State Secretaries of State}}\n{{Arkansas statewide elected officials}}\n\n[[Category:Secretaries of State of Arkansas| ]]\n[[Category:State constitutional officers of Arkansas|Secretary of state]]\n[[Category:1836 establishments in Arkansas]]\n\n\n{{Arkansas-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cabinet officer in the government of the U.S. state of Arkansas}}\n{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = Secretary of State\n|body            = Arkansas\n|insignia        = Seal of Arkansas.svg\n|insigniasize    = 110px\n|insigniacaption = [[Great Seal of Arkansas|State seal]]\n|image           = \n|incumbent       = [[John Thurston (politician)|John Thurston]]\n|incumbentsince  = January 15, 2019\n|style           =\n|appointer       =\n|termlength      = 4 years\n|formation       = [[Constitution of Arkansas|Arkansas Constitution]]<br />1836, 1868 and 1874\n|succession      =\n|inaugural       = Robert A. Watkins<br />1836\n|website         = {{URL|https://www.sos.arkansas.gov/}}\n|salary          = $54,305<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ballotpedia.org/Arkansas_state_government_salary |title=Arkansas state government salary |publisher=Ballotpedia |access-date=February 4, 2018 }}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Secretary of State of Arkansas''' is one of the elected constitutional officers of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Arkansas]].\n\nThe current Secretary of State is the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[John Thurston (politician)|John Thurston]], former [[Arkansas Land Commissioner]] from [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]] in central Arkansas.\n\n==Organization==\nThe Secretary of State's Office is composed of seven divisions:\n\n*The Building & Grounds Division maintains the [[Arkansas State Capitol]] and its surrounding grounds and gardens.\n*The Business & Commercial Services Division is responsible for filing [[lien]]s pursuant to the [[Uniform Commercial Code]], registering [[business entities]] and [[trademark]]s, collecting the state [[franchise tax]], and licensing [[Notary public|notaries public]].\n*The Communications & Education Division provides public education about [[civics]] and the [[History of Arkansas]], and produces various state publications.\n*The Elections Division administers elections, regulates [[campaign finance]] and [[lobbying]], and ensures compliance with state and federal [[election law]]s.\n*The Fiscal Office deals with the internal financial, logistical, and personnel matters of the Office of the Secretary of State.  They also distribute the [[Flag of Arkansas|Arkansas]] and [[Flag of the United States|United States flag]].\n*The Secretary also runs the State Capitol Gift Shop.\n*The State Capitol Police provide security for the State Capitol building and police services for the Capitol Complex.\n\n==Other duties==\nThe Secretary of State also publishes the state's [[Administrative law|administrative regulations]] and the state [[gazette]], the ''Arkansas Register''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sos.arkansas.gov/rules-regulations |publisher=Arkansas Secretary of State |title=Rules & Regulations |access-date=May 10, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Officeholders==\n[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] were elected exclusively to the office of Secretary of State from the later [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction era]] until the retirement of [[Charlie Daniels (politician)|Charlie Daniels]] to run for State Auditor in 2010, when the first modern-day Republican to hold the office, Mark Martin, was elected. Secretaries of state during the statehood of Arkansas include:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?search=1&entryID=5723 |title=Office of Secretary of State |website=The Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture |access-date=February 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* [[Robert A. Watkins]] (D) 1836\u20131840\n* [[D. B. Greer]] 1840\u20131842\n* [[John Winfrey]] (D) 1842\n* [[D. B. Greer]] (D) 1842\u20131859\n* [[Alexander Boileau]] (D) 1859\u20131860\n* [[S. W. Weaver]] (D) 1860\n* [[John I. Stirman]] (D/Confederate) 1860\u20131862\n* [[O. H. Oates]] (Confederate) 1862\u20131864\n* [[Robert J. T. White]] (R) 1864\u20131871\n* [[James M. Johnson (Arkansas)|James M. Johnson]] (R) 1871\u20131874\n* [[Benton B. Beavers]] (D) 1874\u20131879\n* [[Jacob Frolich]] (D) 1879\u20131885\n* [[Elias B. Moore]] (D) 1885\u20131889\n* [[B. B. Chism]] (D) 1889\u20131893\n* [[H. B. Armistead]] (D) 1893\u20131897\n* [[Alexander C. Hull]] (D) 1