ive on the historical development of the concept of number.\n\n{{Complex numbers}}\n{{Number systems}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Complex Number}}\n[[Category:Composition algebras]]\n[[Category:Complex numbers| ]]\n", "name_user": "Deacon Vorbis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExponential function:\\sim -> \\approx", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number"}
{"title_page": "Brantford 99ers", "text_new": "{{Pro hockey team\n|bg_color = red\n|text_color = black\n| team        = Brantford 99ers \n| logo        = \n| logosize    = \n| city        = [[Brantford, Ontario]], Canada\n| league      = [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]]\n| division    = West\n| founded     = 1966\n| arena       = [[Wayne Gretzky Sports Centre]]\n| colours     = Red, black, white<br>{{color box|red}} {{color box|black}} {{color box|white}}\n| owner       = Darren DeDobbelaer\n| coach       = Dan Fitzgerald <small>(2018\u201319)</small>\n| GM          = Darren DeDobbelaer\n| affiliates  = Brantford 99ers\n\n| dates1 = 1966\u20131971\n| name1 = Milton Merchants\n| dates2 = 1971\u20131983\n| name2 = Milton Flyers\n| dates3 = 1983\u20131986\n| name3 = Milton Steamers\n| dates4 = 1986\u20132003\n| name4 = Milton Merchants\n| dates5 = 2003\u20132018\n| name5 = Milton Icehawks\n| dates6 = 2018\u2013present\n| name6 = Brantford 99ers\n| championships = '''[[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Buckland Trophy]]: 2''' (1997, 1998)<br>'''[[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]: 1''' (1998)\n}}\n\nThe '''Brantford 99ers''' are a [[Junior ice hockey#Junior A|Junior A]] [[ice hockey]] team from [[Brantford, Ontario]], Canada.  They are a part of the [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]]. The 99ers have previously been known as the Milton Icehawks, Milton Merchants, Milton Flyers, and Milton Steamers as Milton hosted junior hockey from 1966 to 2018. After purchasing the team, Darren DeDobbelaer of Brantford moved the club to that city for the start of the 2018-19 season, re-branding the team as the 99ers.\n\n==History==\nThe Icehawks were one of the most historical teams in the Ontario Junior Hockey League, having been formed in 1964 until the team was purchased and moved to Brantford for the 2018-19 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quintenews.com/2018/06/ojhl-teams-move-cities-divisions-conferences/178975/|title=OJHL teams move cities, divisions & conferences - Quinte News|date=10 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://miltonicehawks.pointstreaksites.com/view/miltonicehawks |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821171120/http://miltonicehawks.pointstreaksites.com/view/miltonicehawks |archive-date=2017-08-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The Icehawks (2003\u20132018) have previously been known as the Milton Flyers (1971-1983), Milton Steamers (1983-1986), and Milton Merchants (1966-1971, 1986-2003).\n\n===Early years===\nAfter serving in the Second World War as a RCAF wireless air gunner, David Brush returned to Milton and managed the Fred Armstrong Arena on Brown Street for two years, before Milton had artificial ice. His dedication to hockey included coaching at the minor league level and founding the town\u2019s first Junior C club, the Milton Merchants, in 1964 as co-owner and president, which later became Jr. B and eventually Jr. A. For his efforts Brush was inducted into the Milton Sports Hall of Fame in 2018.<ref>https://www.milton.ca/en/play/sportshalloffame_Ceremony.asp</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Vern Gooding owned the local team when they were known as the Milton Flyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2499204/page/5?n=3&q=flyers|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 4 Dec 1974, p. 5|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, three players including the team captain and top scorer left the team mid season over an imposed curfew dispute. Two of the three players had had tryouts with OHL clubs, and all three were club veterans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2499208/page/5?n=20&q=flyers|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 30 Dec 1974, p. 5|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nGrant Turner, Mark Grenier, Howie Scannell, and John Morgan owned the Milton Steamers in the early 1980s. Morgan sold his stake in the club to Turner, prompting Scannell to announce that he was preparing to sell his stake as well. On April 10, 1986, Turner, Grenier and Scannell sold the Steamers to Brad Grant who owned trucking company Sandstone Transport.<ref name=\"halinet.on.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2689041/page/10?n=1&q=brad+grant|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 16 Apr 1986, p. 9|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Grant era and championship successes===\nTrucking magnate [[Brad Grant]] purchased the team in April 1986 when it seemed like the organization might fold. For the 1986-87 season, he immediately changed the team's name from the Steamers to the Merchants after the Junior C team of old, and brought in former coach Gerry Inglis, who had also coached the Georgetown Raiders and had won five intermediate championships at the time.<ref name=\"halinet.on.ca\"/>\n\nGrant led the team to tremendous success in the late 1990s. During his 15-year ownership run, the team captured four division crowns, three league championships and a provincial title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/Partners/MPL/MPL002504511pf_0676.pdf |title=Photo |website=images.ourontario.ca |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the Milton Merchants were Central Junior B Hockey League champions with a 4-2 victory in Game 7 over the Aurora Eagles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2690358/page/2|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 3 Apr 1992, p. 1|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>  They made the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] [[Sutherland Cup]] Junior B championship but lost in five games to the [[Mid-Western Junior B Hockey League]]'s [[Kitchener Dutchmen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2690370/page/16|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 1 May 1992, p. 15|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 1992-93 season, the Merchants made the jump to Junior A in the OPJHL.\n\nThe 1994-95 season marked the beginning of a historical run for the franchise as the club won five straight division titles. The surge of success increased when the Merchants were crowned league champions in 1997, winning the [[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Buckland Trophy]] after defeating the [[Newmarket 87's]]. In the 1997 Dudley Cup playoffs, the [[Rayside-Balfour Sabrecats]] (NOJHL) beat Milton four games to one.\n\nIn 1998, the Milton Merchants repeated their Buckland Trophy title, dispatching the [[Newmarket Hurricanes]] this time, and then went on to become Central Canadian Junior A Champions by winning the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]], defeating the [[Rayside-Balfour Sabrecats]] (NOJHL) four games to two, and exacting revenge for the previous year's loss to Rayside-Balfour.\n\nAt the [[1998 Royal Bank Cup]], the Milton Merchants went 1-3 in round robin play. In the semifinal game, Milton lost 6-2 to the [[South Surrey Eagles]] and were eliminated from the tournament.\n\nIn 2018, the Milton Sports Hall of Fame announced that it is inducting the 1996\u201397 and 1997-98 Merchants teams, and Brad Grant as a builder, during a ceremony in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/8698542-2018-class-named-for-milton-sports-hall-of-fame-induction/|title=2018 class named for Milton Sports Hall of Fame induction|date=27 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Forgione era===\nIn 2001, Grant sold the team to an Oakville trio that consisted of ex-NHLer [[Dave Gagner]], Mario Forgione who owned the [[Mississauga IceDogs]] at the time and was an automotive parts manufacturing president, and wine distillery consultant Ken Chase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2507710/page/17|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 15 Mar 2005, p. 17|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2506764/page/22|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 22 Jun 2001, p. 22|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2003-04 season, Forgione changed the team's name from the Merchants to the IceHawks to reflect the team's connection with the local minor hockey programs called the Winterhawks, and Forgione's ownership of the Mississauga IceDogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2507362/page/21|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 17 Jun 2003, p. 21|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref> In 2005, the Ontario Hockey Association fined the Icehawks $12,000 and suspended then-General Manager George Dupont for signing two players outside of OHA guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chathamdailynews.ca/2010/12/10/junior-hockeys-dirty-little-ecret |title=Chatham News, Sports, Entertainment, Business, Life & Opinion &#124; Chatham Daily News |publisher=Chathamdailynews.ca |date= |accessdate=2018-09-05}}</ref> In 2006, Forgione officially affiliated the Icehawks with the IceDogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508127/page/15?n=|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 14 Mar 2006, p. 15|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Heinz era===\nIn the spring of 2006, ex-NHL goaltender [[Rick Heinz|Rick Heinz']] attempt to purchase the nearby [[Georgetown Raiders]] fell through, but by July 2006 the local Campbellville resident Heinz had talked Forgione into selling the Icehawks, and the affiliation with the IceDogs ended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508247/page/18?n=|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 7 Jul 2006, p. 18|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref> Heinz sold the team just nine months later after starting the season with essentially no committed players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508366/page/19|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 30 Mar 2007, p. 19|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===DeVincentis and Piett era===\nDean Piett, a commercial real estate businessman from Burlington, and Rob DeVincentis, the Ancaster owner of a construction business, purchased the team from Heinz and owned the team from 2007 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/Partners/MPL/MPL002508887pf_0884.pdf |title=Photo |website=images.ourontario.ca |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n===Move to Brantford===\nDeVincentis sold the team in 2017 to Darren DeDobbelaer of Brantford, whose son Eric played on the Junior B Brantford 99ers, which DeDobbelaer also owned. The Ontario Hockey Association originally blocked the $500,000 sale of the IceHawks to prevent DeDobbelaer from moving the team to Brantford, or promoting the 99ers to Jr. A and demoting the IceHawks in Milton to Jr. B. Complicating matters was the fact that Brad Grant who previously owned the team was OHA chairman at the time of the proposed sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hamiltonnews.com/news-story/7410289-oha-decision-ices-bid-to-bring-junior-hockey-back-to-the-mountain/|title=OHA decision ices bid to bring junior hockey back to the Mountain|first=Mark|last=Newman|date=6 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The sale was ultimately approved on the condition that the IceHawks remain in Milton for the 2017\u201318 season. The team the announced that starting in the 2018\u201319 season the team would relocate to Brantford to play under the 99ers name with the OJHL's approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/7505077-milton-must-support-icehawks-to-keep-them-says-new-owner/|title=Milton must support IceHawks to keep them, says new owner|first=Steve|last=LeBlanc|date=16 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> However, this move was denied by the [[Ontario Hockey Association]], the overseeing organization for the [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]], by refusing to send officials to their first game in Brantford on September 13<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pointstreaksites.com/view/ojhl/news-21/news_509272 |title=OJHL POSTPONES TONIGHT'S GAME IN BRANTFORD |publisher=OJHL |date=13 September 2018}}</ref> and the Icehawks were forced to stay in Milton for another season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pointstreaksites.com/view/ojhl/news-21/news_509352 |title=OJHL Update |publisher=OJHL |date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, the OHA and OJHL announced the relocation of the team back to Brantford.<ref>https://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/sports/local-sports/jr-a-99ers-return-to-brantford</ref>\n\n==Season-by-season results==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#ddd;\"\n|'''Season'''\t||'''GP''' || '''W''' || '''L''' || '''T''' || '''OTL''' || '''GF''' ||\t'''GA''' || '''P''' || '''Results''' || '''Playoffs'''\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1970-71\t||33    ||12   ||17   ||4   ||-    ||147   ||166    ||28\t||7th MOJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1971-72\t||42    ||13   ||20   ||9   ||-    ||171   ||231    ||35\t||5th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1972-73\t||42    ||9    ||30   ||3   ||-    ||171   ||278    ||21\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1973-74\t||42    ||25    ||10   ||7   ||-    ||246   ||174    ||57\t||2nd CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1974-75\t||colspan=\"11\"|Statistics Not Available\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1975-76\t||36    ||12    ||21   ||3   ||-    ||167   ||237    ||27\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1976-77\t||42    ||17    ||22   ||3   ||-    ||206   ||237    ||37\t||6th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1977-78\t||42    ||20   ||16   ||6   ||-    ||--    ||--     ||46\t||4th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1978-79\t||44    ||16   ||23   ||5   ||-    ||205    ||277     ||37\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1979-80\t||44\t||10\t||28\t||5\t||-\t||192\t||298\t||25\t||11th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1980-81\t||44\t||4\t||37\t||3\t||-\t||184\t||337\t||11\t||12th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1981-82\t||40\t||6\t||30\t||4\t||-\t||156\t||303\t||16\t||11th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1982-83\t||42\t||18\t||18\t||6\t||-\t||200\t||233\t||42\t||5th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1983-84\t||40\t||12\t||23\t||5\t||-\t||182\t||200\t||29\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1984-85\t||40\t||20\t||16\t||4\t||-\t||193\t||166\t||44\t||5th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1985-86\t||48\t||5\t||37\t||6\t||-\t||173\t||354\t||16\t||9th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1986-87\t||42\t||9\t||29\t||4\t||-\t||158\t||278\t||22\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1987-88\t||44\t||18\t||22\t||4\t||-\t||232\t||250\t||40\t||9th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1988-89\t||42\t||12\t||26\t||4\t||-\t||164\t||250\t||28\t||12th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1989-90\t||42\t||18\t||17\t||7\t||-\t||189\t||181\t||43\t||6th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1990-91\t||42\t||25\t||10\t||7\t||-\t||265\t||184\t||57\t||3rd CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1991-92\t||42\t||29\t||8\t||5\t||-\t||207\t||138\t||63\t||2nd CJBHL\t||[[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Won League]]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1992-93\t||49\t||32\t||15\t||2\t||-\t||269\t||190\t||68\t||5th CJBHL||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1993\u201394 OPJHL season|1993-94]] ||42 \t||24 \t||16 \t||2 \t||- \t||228 \t||183 \t||52\t||5th OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1994\u201395 OPJHL season|1994-95]] ||49 \t||33 \t||14 \t||2 \t||- \t||287 \t||226 \t||69 \t||1st OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1995\u201396 OPJHL season|1995-96]] ||50 \t||27 \t||16 \t||7 \t||- \t||243 \t||172 \t||64 \t||1st OPJHL-Mi||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1996\u201397 OPJHL season|1996-97]] ||51 \t||37 \t||9 \t||5 \t||- \t||319 \t||169 \t||81 \t||1st OPJHL-Mi\t||[[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Won League]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1997\u201398 OPJHL season|1997-98]] ||51  \t||42  \t||8  \t||1  \t||0  \t||357  \t||127  \t||85  \t||1st OPJHL-Mi\t||[[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Won League]], Won [[Dudley Hewitt Cup|DHC]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1998\u201399 OPJHL season|1998-99]] ||51  \t||43  \t||4  \t||3  \t||1  \t||308  \t||138  \t||90  \t||1st OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1999\u20132000 OPJHL season|1999-00]] ||49 \t||30 \t||13 \t||3 \t||3 \t||231 \t||158 \t||66 \t||3rd OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2000\u201301 OPJHL season|2000-01]] ||49 \t||29 \t||14 \t||5 \t||1 \t||210 \t||168 \t||64 \t||1st OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2001\u201302 OPJHL season|2001-02]] ||49 \t||25 \t||20 \t||3 \t||1 \t||198 \t||208 \t||54 \t||5th OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2002\u201303 OPJHL season|2002-03]] ||49 \t||41 \t||6 \t||1 \t||1 \t||279 \t||139 \t||84 \t||1st OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2003\u201304 OPJHL season|2003-04]] ||49 \t||32 \t||15 \t||0 \t||2 \t||228 \t||161 \t||66 \t||4th OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2004\u201305 OPJHL season|2004-05]] ||49 \t||30 \t||17 \t||1 \t||1 \t||241 \t||131 \t||62 \t||4th OPJHL-W||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2005\u201306 OPJHL season|2005-06]] ||49  \t||41  \t||3  \t||4  \t||1  \t||254  \t||97  \t||87  \t||1st OPJHL-W\t||Lost Conf. SF\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2006\u201307 OPJHL season|2006-07]] ||49   ||12    ||31    ||4     ||2     ||142   ||235   ||30    ||8th OPJHL-W    ||Lost Conf. QF\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2007-08     ||49    ||22   ||20   ||-   ||7    ||185   ||194    ||51\t||6th OPJHL-W ||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2008-09\t||49    ||21   ||24   ||-   ||4    ||208   ||229    ||46\t||6th OJHL-M||\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2009-10\t||56    ||3    ||51   ||-   ||2    ||145   ||387    ||8    ||15th OJAHL   ||DNQ\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2010-11\t||50    ||5    ||41   ||-   ||4    ||147   ||374    ||14   ||8th OJHL-W   ||DNQ\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2011-12\t||49    ||18   ||28   ||-   ||3    ||195   ||264    ||39   ||5th OJHL-W   ||Lost Division QF\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2012-13\t||55    ||19   ||27   ||-   ||9    ||209   ||255    ||47   ||4th OJHL-W   ||DNQ\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2013-14\t||53    ||29   ||20   ||-   ||3    ||186   ||193    ||61   ||3rd OJHL-W  ||Lost Conf. QF\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2014-15\t||-   ||-   ||-   ||-   ||-    ||-   ||-    ||-    ||- ||-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2015-16\t||54    ||5   ||48   ||0   ||1    ||110   ||362    ||11    ||<small>5th of 5 West Div<br>11th of 11 SW Conf<br>22nd of 22 OJHL</small> ||DNQ\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2016-17\t||54    ||4   ||48   ||1   ||1    ||125   ||385    ||10    ||<small>5th of 5 West Div<br>11th of 11 SW Conf<br>22nd of 22 OJHL</small> ||DNQ\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|2017-18\t||54    ||4   ||47   ||0   ||3    ||125   ||385    ||11    ||<small>5th of 5 West Div<br>11th of 11 SW Conf<br>22nd of 22 OJHL</small> ||DNQ\n|}\n\n==Sutherland Cup appearances==\n:''1992'': '''[[Kitchener Dutchmen]]''' defeated Milton Merchants ''4-games-to-1''\n\n==Notable alumni==\nMany notable players have suited up for Milton over the years including NHL stars [[John Tavares (ice hockey)|John Tavares]], [[Daniel Carcillo]], [[Sam Gagner]], [[Rich Peverley]], [[Darren Haydar]], [[Cody Goloubef]] and [[Matt Read]].\n\nSome famous Miltonians have also played for the franchise, including four-time Stanley Cup champion [[John Tonelli]], AHL star [[Darren Haydar]], two-time NCAA Frozen Four champion Boston College captain Matt Price, and his brother Jeremy Price (Vancouver Canucks' draft pick).\n\n*[[Akim Aliu]]\n*[[John Tonelli]]\n*[[Daniel Carcillo]]\n*[[Jay Caufield]]\n*[[Jeff Daw]]\n*[[Sam Gagner]]\n*[[Darren Haydar]]\n*[[John Tavares (ice hockey)|John Tavares]]\n*[[Matt Read]]\n*[[Rich Peverley]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://brantford.pointstreaksites.com/view/brantford  99ers website]\n\n{{clear|right}}\n{{OPJAHL}}\n{{Toronto Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Milton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Ontario Provincial Junior A Hockey League teams]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey clubs established in 1966]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Pro hockey team\n|bg_color = red\n|text_color = black\n| team        = Brantford 99ers \n| logo        = \n| logosize    = \n| city        = [[Brantford, Ontario]], Canada\n| league      = [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]]\n| division    = West\n| founded     = 1966\n| arena       = [[Wayne Gretzky Sports Centre]]\n| colours     = Red, black, white<br>{{color box|red}} {{color box|black}} {{color box|white}}\n| owner       = Darren DeDobbelaer\n| coach       = Dan Fitzgerald <small>(2018\u201319)</small>\n| GM          = Darren DeDobbelaer\n| affiliates  = Brantford 99ers\n\n| dates1 = 1966\u20131971\n| name1 = Milton Merchants\n| dates2 = 1971\u20131983\n| name2 = Milton Flyers\n| dates3 = 1983\u20131986\n| name3 = Milton Steamers\n| dates4 = 1986\u20132003\n| name4 = Milton Merchants\n| dates5 = 2003\u20132018\n| name5 = Milton Icehawks\n| dates6 = 2018\u2013present\n| name6 = Brantford 99ers\n| championships = '''[[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Buckland Trophy]]: 2''' (1997, 1998)<br>'''[[Dudley Hewitt Cup]]: 1''' (1998)\n}}\n\nThe '''Brantford 99ers''' are a [[Junior ice hockey#Junior A|Junior A]] [[ice hockey]] team from [[Brantford, Ontario]], Canada.  They are a part of the [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]]. The 99ers have previously been known as the Milton Icehawks, Milton Merchants, Milton Flyers, and Milton Steamers as Milton hosted junior hockey from 1966 to 2018. After purchasing the team, Darren DeDobbelaer of Brantford moved the club to that city for the start of the 2018-19 season, re-branding the team as the 99ers.\n\n==History==\nThe Icehawks were one of the most historical teams in the Ontario Junior Hockey League, having been formed in 1964 until the team was purchased and moved to Brantford for the 2018-19 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quintenews.com/2018/06/ojhl-teams-move-cities-divisions-conferences/178975/|title=OJHL teams move cities, divisions & conferences - Quinte News|date=10 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://miltonicehawks.pointstreaksites.com/view/miltonicehawks |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821171120/http://miltonicehawks.pointstreaksites.com/view/miltonicehawks |archive-date=2017-08-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The Icehawks (2003\u20132018) have previously been known as the Milton Flyers (1971-1983), Milton Steamers (1983-1986), and Milton Merchants (1966-1971, 1986-2003).\n\n===Early years===\nAfter serving in the Second World War as a RCAF wireless air gunner, David Brush returned to Milton and managed the Fred Armstrong Arena on Brown Street for two years, before Milton had artificial ice. His dedication to hockey included coaching at the minor league level and founding the town\u2019s first Junior C club, the Milton Merchants, in 1964 as co-owner and president, which later became Jr. B and eventually Jr. A. For his efforts Brush was inducted into the Milton Sports Hall of Fame in 2018.<ref>https://www.milton.ca/en/play/sportshalloffame_Ceremony.asp</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Vern Gooding owned the local team when they were known as the Milton Flyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2499204/page/5?n=3&q=flyers|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 4 Dec 1974, p. 5|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, three players including the team captain and top scorer left the team mid season over an imposed curfew dispute. Two of the three players had had tryouts with OHL clubs, and all three were club veterans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2499208/page/5?n=20&q=flyers|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 30 Dec 1974, p. 5|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nGrant Turner, Mark Grenier, Howie Scannell, and John Morgan owned the Milton Steamers in the early 1980s. Morgan sold his stake in the club to Turner, prompting Scannell to announce that he was preparing to sell his stake as well. On April 10, 1986, Turner, Grenier and Scannell sold the Steamers to Brad Grant who owned trucking company Sandstone Transport.<ref name=\"halinet.on.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2689041/page/10?n=1&q=brad+grant|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 16 Apr 1986, p. 9|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Grant era and championship successes===\nTrucking magnate [[Brad Grant]] purchased the team in April 1986 when it seemed like the organization might fold. For the 1986-87 season, he immediately changed the team's name from the Steamers to the Merchants after the Junior C team of old, and brought in former coach Gerry Inglis, who had also coached the Georgetown Raiders and had won five intermediate championships at the time.<ref name=\"halinet.on.ca\"/>\n\nGrant led the team to tremendous success in the late 1990s. During his 15-year ownership run, the team captured four division crowns, three league championships and a provincial title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/Partners/MPL/MPL002504511pf_0676.pdf |title=Photo |website=images.ourontario.ca |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the Milton Merchants were Central Junior B Hockey League champions with a 4-2 victory in Game 7 over the Aurora Eagles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2690358/page/2|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 3 Apr 1992, p. 1|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>  They made the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] [[Sutherland Cup]] Junior B championship but lost in five games to the [[Mid-Western Junior B Hockey League]]'s [[Kitchener Dutchmen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2690370/page/16|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 1 May 1992, p. 15|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 1992-93 season, the Merchants made the jump to Junior A in the OPJHL.\n\nThe 1994-95 season marked the beginning of a historical run for the franchise as the club won five straight division titles. The surge of success increased when the Merchants were crowned league champions in 1997, winning the [[Frank L. Buckland Trophy|Buckland Trophy]] after defeating the [[Newmarket 87's]]. In the 1997 Dudley Cup playoffs, the [[Rayside-Balfour Sabrecats]] (NOJHL) beat Milton four games to one.\n\nIn 1998, the Milton Merchants repeated their Buckland Trophy title, dispatching the [[Newmarket Hurricanes]] this time, and then went on to become Central Canadian Junior A Champions by winning the [[Dudley Hewitt Cup]], defeating the [[Rayside-Balfour Sabrecats]] (NOJHL) four games to two, and exacting revenge for the previous year's loss to Rayside-Balfour.\n\nAt the [[1998 Royal Bank Cup]], the Milton Merchants went 1-3 in round robin play. In the semifinal game, Milton lost 6-2 to the [[South Surrey Eagles]] and were eliminated from the tournament.\n\nIn 2018, the Milton Sports Hall of Fame announced that it is inducting the 1996\u201397 and 1997-98 Merchants teams, and Brad Grant as a builder, during a ceremony in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/8698542-2018-class-named-for-milton-sports-hall-of-fame-induction/|title=2018 class named for Milton Sports Hall of Fame induction|date=27 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Forgione era===\nIn 2001, Grant sold the team to an Oakville trio that consisted of ex-NHLer [[Dave Gagner]], Mario Forgione who owned the [[Mississauga IceDogs]] at the time and was an automotive parts manufacturing president, and wine distillery consultant Ken Chase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2507710/page/17|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 15 Mar 2005, p. 17|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2506764/page/22|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 22 Jun 2001, p. 22|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2003-04 season, Forgione changed the team's name from the Merhcants to the IceHawks to reflect the team's connection with the local minor hockey programs called the Winterhawks, and Forgione's ownership of the Mississauga IceDogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2507362/page/21|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 17 Jun 2003, p. 21|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref> In 2005, the Ontario Hockey Association fined the Icehawks $12,000 and suspended then-General Manager George Dupont for signing two players outside of OHA guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chathamdailynews.ca/2010/12/10/junior-hockeys-dirty-little-ecret |title=Chatham News, Sports, Entertainment, Business, Life & Opinion &#124; Chatham Daily News |publisher=Chathamdailynews.ca |date= |accessdate=2018-09-05}}</ref> In 2006, Forgione officially affiliated the Icehawks with the IceDogs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508127/page/15?n=|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 14 Mar 2006, p. 15|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Heinz era===\nIn the spring of 2006, ex-NHL goaltender [[Rick Heinz|Rick Heinz']] attempt to purchase the nearby [[Georgetown Raiders]] fell through, but by July 2006 the local Campbellville resident Heinz had talked Forgione into selling the Icehawks, and the affiliation with the IceDogs ended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508247/page/18?n=|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 7 Jul 2006, p. 18|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref> Heinz sold the team just nine months later after starting the season with essentially no committed players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.milton.halinet.on.ca/2508366/page/19|title=Canadian Champion (Milton, ON), 30 Mar 2007, p. 19|website=news.milton.halinet.on.ca}}</ref>\n\n===DeVincentis and Piett era===\nDean Piett, a commercial real estate businessman from Burlington, and Rob DeVincentis, the Ancaster owner of a construction business, purchased the team from Heinz and owned the team from 2007 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.ourontario.ca/Partners/MPL/MPL002508887pf_0884.pdf |title=Photo |website=images.ourontario.ca |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n===Move to Brantford===\nDeVincentis sold the team in 2017 to Darren DeDobbelaer of Brantford, whose son Eric played on the Junior B Brantford 99ers, which DeDobbelaer also owned. The Ontario Hockey Association originally blocked the $500,000 sale of the IceHawks to prevent DeDobbelaer from moving the team to Brantford, or promoting the 99ers to Jr. A and demoting the IceHawks in Milton to Jr. B. Complicating matters was the fact that Brad Grant who previously owned the team was OHA chairman at the time of the proposed sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hamiltonnews.com/news-story/7410289-oha-decision-ices-bid-to-bring-junior-hockey-back-to-the-mountain/|title=OHA decision ices bid to bring junior hockey back to the Mountain|first=Mark|last=Newman|date=6 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The sale was ultimately approved on the condition that the IceHawks remain in Milton for the 2017\u201318 season. The team the announced that starting in the 2018\u201319 season the team would relocate to Brantford to play under the 99ers name with the OJHL's approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/community-story/7505077-milton-must-support-icehawks-to-keep-them-says-new-owner/|title=Milton must support IceHawks to keep them, says new owner|first=Steve|last=LeBlanc|date=16 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> However, this move was denied by the [[Ontario Hockey Association]], the overseeing organization for the [[Ontario Junior Hockey League]], by refusing to send officials to their first game in Brantford on September 13<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pointstreaksites.com/view/ojhl/news-21/news_509272 |title=OJHL POSTPONES TONIGHT'S GAME IN BRANTFORD |publisher=OJHL |date=13 September 2018}}</ref> and the Icehawks were forced to stay in Milton for another season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pointstreaksites.com/view/ojhl/news-21/news_509352 |title=OJHL Update |publisher=OJHL |date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, the OHA and OJHL announced the relocation of the team back to Brantford.<ref>https://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/sports/local-sports/jr-a-99ers-return-to-brantford</ref>\n\n==Season-by-season results==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#ddd;\"\n|'''Season'''\t||'''GP''' || '''W''' || '''L''' || '''T''' || '''OTL''' || '''GF''' ||\t'''GA''' || '''P''' || '''Results''' || '''Playoffs'''\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1970-71\t||33    ||12   ||17   ||4   ||-    ||147   ||166    ||28\t||7th MOJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1971-72\t||42    ||13   ||20   ||9   ||-    ||171   ||231    ||35\t||5th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1972-73\t||42    ||9    ||30   ||3   ||-    ||171   ||278    ||21\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1973-74\t||42    ||25    ||10   ||7   ||-    ||246   ||174    ||57\t||2nd CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1974-75\t||colspan=\"11\"|Statistics Not Available\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1975-76\t||36    ||12    ||21   ||3   ||-    ||167   ||237    ||27\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1976-77\t||42    ||17    ||22   ||3   ||-    ||206   ||237    ||37\t||6th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1977-78\t||42    ||20   ||16   ||6   ||-    ||--    ||--     ||46\t||4th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#eee;\"\n|1978-79\t||44    ||16   ||23   ||5   ||-    ||205    ||277     ||37\t||7th CJBHL||\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#