{"title_page": "Hult Prize", "text_new": "{{short description|international prize for social enterprise}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name         = Hult Prize\n| image        = Hult Prize Foundation.png\n| description  = \n| presenter    = [[Hult International Business School]]\n| year         = {{Flatlist|\n* {{start date and age|df=yes|2010}}\n}}\n| reward      = $1 million [[United States Dollar|USD]] prize\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.hultprize.org/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hult Prize''' was established by [[Bertil Hult]], and is an annual, year-long competition that crowd-sources ideas from MBA and college students after challenging them to solve a pressing social issue around topics such as food security, water access, energy, and education.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/bertil-hult/ | magazine=Forbes | title=Profile - Bertil Hult}}</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonathan-littman/milliondollar-hunger-real_b_2814157.html Million dollar hunger reality show: The Hult Prize], Huffington Post, 3/7/2013</ref> The Hult family \u2013 founders of EF Education First \u2013 donates US$1 million in seed capital to help the winning team launch a social enterprise.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/02/03/founder-bertil-hult-sees-education-first-breaking-down-global-barriers/KK6hpFwDqvocR73w0Xf9jO/story.html Education First aims to bridge barriers with exchange], Boston Globe, 2/4/2013</ref>\n\nThe Prize is a partnership between [[Hult International Business School]] and the [[United Nations Foundation]]. Former U.S. president [[Bill Clinton]] selects the challenge topic and announces the winner each September; he mentioned it in a 2012 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' article about \"the top 5 ideas that are changing the world for the better\".<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2125031-6,00.html The case for optimism], ''Time'', 10/1/2012</ref><ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/president-bill-clinton-awards-usd1m-hult-prize-at-united-nations-headquarters-to-four-college-students-from-the-uk-for-innovative-rice-farming-startup--issues-10th-anniversary-youth-challenge-300714747.html Cision - President Bill Clinton Awards USD1M Hult Prize at United Nations Headquarters]</ref> The Hult prize has been referred to as the \"Nobel Prize for students\" by Nobel laureate [[Muhammad Yunus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/07/tackling-cavities-in-indias-slums-with-xylitol-gum/|title=Tackling Cavities in India's Slums with Xylitol Gum|last=Higa|first=Liriel|date=2014-11-07|website=On the Ground|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nA lecture given by [[One Laptop Per Child]] director [[Chuck Kane]] sparked the idea for a business case competition focused on solving global problems via social entrepreneurship. In March 2010, MBA students Ahmad Ashkar, Tamara Sam, Carolin Bachmann, Jose Escobar and Nabil Chaachou, launched the Hult Global Case Challenge, later renamed the Hult Prize.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/video/creating-the-next-wave-of-social-entrepreneurs-mKQuhLy4QHSokxb1~JOEcQ.html Creating the next wave of social entrepreneurs], Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Bloomberg TV\u2019s Taking Stock with Pimm Fox, 5/30/2013 {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref> Students from over ninety business schools competed at three Hult campuses in Dubai, London and Boston simultaneously.\n\nIn 2011, the competition expanded into five regional rounds at Hult campuses around the globe (Shanghai, Dubai, London, Boston and San Francisco) with the winning team from each region continuing to the Global Finals in New York City. President Bill Clinton first announced the Hult Prize Winner (still called the Hult Global Case Challenge at the time) in 2011, and has done so in each subsequent year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/eyes-on-prize-ahmad-ashkar-592285.html|title=Eyes on the prize: Ahmad Ashkar|last=King|first=Neil|website=ArabianBusiness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> In 2012, the competition expanded to include three tracks - energy, housing and education - and the Global Final was held at the New York Public Library. By 2013, the Prize attracted more than 10,000 MBA and undergraduate applicants.<ref>http://video.foxnews.com/v/2421703863001/, Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Fox News, 5/30/2013.</ref>\n\nMany major business schools run internal competitions to pre-qualify teams, which they then send into the competition. In 2018, 115,000 students from over 100 countries participated in the Hult Prize, competing for a total of $5m in prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4318dc28-5a97-11e8-806a-808d194ffb75|title=What does it take to win a business plan competition?|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n\n=== Leadership ===\nAhmad Ashkar has served as Founding CEO of the Hult Prize since 2009.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other members of the current leadership team are Karim Samra (COO), Charlemagne Quinitio (Vice-President, Global Operations and Finance), Nelly Andrade (Global Director, Hult Prize On-Campus Program), Jamal Khayyat (Head of Global Business Development), Callum Porter-Harris (Global Director of Regionals), Ayman Arandi (National Program Director), Ricardo Alvarez (Head of Global Brand & Communications) and Priya Sultan (Global Projects Director).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/about/|title=About|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Programs ===\nSince its launch in 2010, Hult has launched several programs. The original competition is now the Hult Prize Flagship Competition, with other programs being the Hult Prize Regionals, Hult Prize on Campus, the Hult Prize Accelerator and the Hult Prize Summit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/faqs/|title=Frequently Asked Questions|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n== Competitions ==\n\n=== 2010: Early childhood education ===\n[[File:One Laptop Per Child at Holmes Elementary (11292383786).jpg|thumb|Children with laptops from [[One Laptop per Child|One Laptop Per Child]], a non-profit organization and the case study of the 2010 inaugural Hult Global Case Challenge. ]]\nThe inaugural Hult Prize was held as The Global Case Challenge and participants sought ways to support and scale the impact of [[One Laptop per Child|One Laptop Per Child]]'s mission in developing, producing and distributing affordable laptops, particularly for developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2010-challenge/|title=2010 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011: Global water crisis ===\nIn 2011, the Hult competition focused on the topic of clean water. Participants were challenged to provide and improve clean water and sanitation ways for the more than 2.5 billion people worldwide, that don't have access to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2011-challenge/|title=2011 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> The competition was held in partnership with [[Matt Damon]] and [[Water.org]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1760918/can-matt-damon-bring-clean-water-africa|title=Can Matt Damon Bring Clean Water To Africa?|author=Fast Company Staff|date=2011-06-20|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> The prize was awarded to a team from [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]], led by [[Akanksha Hazari]], with their proposal turning into the social enterprise [[m.Paani]], working on digital ways to provide safe water, education, healthcare, energy, nutrition and mobility to rural Indian communities.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessweekly.co.uk/news/academia-research/cambridge-stars-clinton%E2%80%99s-1m-social-challenge|title=Cambridge stars in Clinton\u2019s $1m social challenge {{!}} Business Weekly {{!}} Technology News {{!}} Business news {{!}} Cambridge and the East of England|website=www.businessweekly.co.uk|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012: Housing, education and energy ===\nIn 2012, the Hult competition revolved around global energy poverty, seeking to support the many people worldwide, that still live without electricity. The challenge was focused on removing the use of kerosene lamps in Africa by 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2012-challenge/|title=2012 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> The winner was a group from [[New York University Abu Dhabi]], consisting of international students. The group was priced for their solution to supply solar lighting. To apply the student's ideas, [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] [[SolarAid]] was awarded with a part of the prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyuad.nyu.edu/en/news/latest-news/honors-and-awards/2012/april/nyuad-team-wins-hult-global-case-challenge.html|title=NYUAD Team Wins Hult Global Case Challenge|last=Dhabi|first=NYU Abu|website=New York University Abu Dhabi|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013: The Global Food Crisis ===\nDue to the fact that nearly one billion people worldwide are still suffering from hunger, the Hult Prize 2013 focused on the Global Food Crisis. The 2013 topic was personally chosen by Bill Clinton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2013-challenge/|title=2013 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> The prize went to Aspire Food from [[McGill University]] for the idea of processing edible insects to produce a sustainable source of protein. This way providing slum communities with an easier and better access to essential nutrients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/author/hult-prize-team-mcgill|title=Hult Prize: Team McGill {{!}} HuffPost|website=www.huffpost.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014: Solving Non-Communicable Disease in the Urban Slum ===\nThe 2014 Hult Prize concentrated on Healthcare: Non-Communicable Disease in the Urban Slums. The students were challenged to build sustainable and scalable social enterprises to fight again non-communicable disease in slums.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2014-challenge/|title=2014 Challenge|date=2017-03-29|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The prize was awarded to a group of five alumni from [[Indian School of Business]] (ISB). The winning team, [[NanoHealth|Nano Health]], suggested the education and employment of health workers, who would run screening camps, help to diagnose diseases and support citizens in lifestyle changes. The health workers were equipped with \"Doc-in-a-Box\" \u2013 a diagnostic tool for basic health indicators. Nano Health is supported from various industrial partners, including GVK Biosciences, who supported with project with their tool HEART (Health Emphasized Analytical and Reporting Tool).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isb.edu/news-media/isb-updates/isb-team-wins-hult-prize-and-usd-1-million-in-prize-money|title=ISB Team wins Hult Prize and USD 1 million in prize money from HULT and Clinton Foundation {{!}} Indian School of Business (ISB)|website=www.isb.edu|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== 2015: Early Childhood Education ===\nIn 2015, the prize challenged teams to find solutions for the early childhood education gap (0\u20136 years old kids).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2015-challenge/|title=2015 Challenge|date=2017-03-29|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> The winning team was IMPCT from the IMBA Program at [[National Chengchi University]] in [[Taiwan]]. The team developed PlayCare, a micro-equity platform, where everyone can invest in sustainable education businesses under a profit-sharing-model. The education businesses, like care centers in urban slums, supports also with educational efforts and increasing enrollment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://imba.nccu.edu.tw/en/news/IMPCT-Wins-the-2015-Hult-Prize-Finals-84239310|title=IMPCT Wins the 2015 Hult Prize Finals!|website=IMBA, NCCU|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> The team also named [[Ann Louie Li]] their Founding Ambassador, who pioneered  the social media movement 'Creating an #IMPCT'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ent.abs-cbn.com/pbbseason7/articles-photos/61090517-remember-the-other-half-of-jamli-love-team-heres-a-photo-update-about-ann-li-2492|title=Remember the other half of #JamLi love team? Here's a photo update about Ann Li! {{!}} ABS-CBN Entertainment|website=ent.abs-cbn.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://firstclasse.com.my/rich-heirs-on-instagram-ann-louie-li/|title=Rich Heirs on Instagram: Ann Louie Li, the globetrotting Forbes 30 under 30 multihyphenate|date=2020-02-27|website=FirstClasse|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016: Crowded urban spaces  ===\nThe 2016 Hult Prize challenge for teams participating was to present the idea for a business that would double the income of 1 million people in the developing world by 2022. The prize was awarded to a team from [[Earlham College]] whose business idea, Magic Bus Ticketing, focused on improving the public transportation system in Kenya.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/devinthorpe/2016/10/05/hult-prize-winners-to-deploy-1m-prize-improving-public-transit-in-kenya/|title=Hult Prize Winners To Deploy $1M Prize Improving Public Transit In Kenya|last=Thorpe|first=Devin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\nJudges at the 2016 competition were: [[Mohammed Ashour]], CEO of [[Aspire Food Group]], [[Robert Collymore|Bob Collymore]], CEO of [[Safaricom]], [[Brian Fetherstonhaugh]], Chairman & CEO of OgilvyOne, Kathleen Rogers, President of Earth Day, [[Premal Shah]], President and co-founder of Kiva and [[Muhammad Yunus]], 2006 Nobel Peace Prize recipient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2017-Hult-Prize-Media-Kit.pdf|title=Hult Prize Media Kit (2017)}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017: Refugees \u2013 Reawakening Human Potential ===\nIn 2017, the Hult competition centered the motion of humanity, and the ensuing massive demographic shifts, which pressure social, political, and physical infrastructures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2017-challenge/|title=2017 Challenge|date=2017-03-28|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> The Competition was won by TeamEME from [[College of Electrical and Mechanical Engineering|EME College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pakwired.com/hult-prize-competition-2017-teameme-of-nust-wins-to-represent-pakistan-in-regional-finals-in-dubai/|title=Hult Prize Competition 2017 - TeamEME Wins to Represent Pakistan in Regional Finals in Dubai|last=Rasheed|first=Mohsin|date=2017-01-07|website=PakWired - Latest Startup and Technology News from Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Transform \u2013 Harnessing the Power of Energy ===\nIn 2018, the prize challenged student teams to find and evolve energy innovations to enhance million of lives. The Hult Prize assumes, that it is necessary for the world to find more disruption that taps into energy innovations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/current/2018-challenge/|title=2018 Challenge|date=2017-09-21|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>  The competition was won by team SunRice from University College London.\n\n*\n\n== Partnerships ==\nIn 2010, the competition focused on education in partnership with One Laptop Per Child.<ref>[http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html Top business school students to compete for innovative solution to educate 2 billion poor kids] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030002208/http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html |date=2010-10-30 }}, Chinastakes.com, 2/25/2010</ref> The 2011 event partnered with [[water.org]] to focus on the provision of clean water.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8c9679f4-f0b0-11df-8cc5-00144feab49a.html Matt Damon\u2019s charity benefits from global MBA advice], Financial Times, 11/15/2010</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n[https://rajmarga.com/hult-prize-at-iost-tribhuvan-university/ Hult Prize At IOST, Tribhuvan University]- Rajmarga.com\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news|last1=Mazzoni|first1=Mary|title=The Hult Prize: Incubating for Impact|url=http://www.triplepundit.com/2016/11/ahmad-ashkar-hult-prize-describes-company-future/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=Triple Pundit|date=8 November 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Melby|first1=Caleb|title=Hult Global Case Challenge Is Changing The Social Business Paradigm|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/calebmelby/2012/04/30/hult-global-case-challenge-is-changing-the-social-business-paradigm/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=Forbes|date=30 April 2012}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Woodward|first1=Vivienne|title=The $1 Million \"Nobel Prize\" For Social Entrepreneurs Now Dedicated To Refugees|url=https://money.good.is/articles/hult-prize-refugee-aid|accessdate=11 April 2017|publisher=GOOD Money|date=7 April 2017}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Bahree|first1=Megha|title=A million dollars to solve the world's problems|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2015/01/11/ozy-million-dollars-solve-world-problems/21501745/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=USA Today|date=11 January 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.hultprize.org/ Official website]\n\n{{Hult}}\n\n[[Category:Competitions]]\n[[Category:Social entrepreneurship]]\n[[Category:Competitions by country]]\n[[Category:Competitions in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|international prize for social enterprise}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name         = Hult Prize\n| image        = Hult Prize Foundation.png\n| description  = \n| presenter    = [[Hult International Business School]]\n| year         = {{Flatlist|\n* {{start date and age|df=yes|2010}}\n}}\n| reward      = $1 million [[United States Dollar|USD]] prize\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.hultprize.org/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hult Prize''' was established by [[Bertil Hult]], and is an annual, year-long competition that crowd-sources ideas from MBA and college students after challenging them to solve a pressing social issue around topics such as food security, water access, energy, and education.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/bertil-hult/ | publisher=Forbes | title=Profile - Bertil Hult}}</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonathan-littman/milliondollar-hunger-real_b_2814157.html Million dollar hunger reality show: The Hult Prize], Huffington Post, 3/7/2013</ref> The Hult family \u2013 founders of EF Education First \u2013 donates USD 1 million in seed capital to help the winning team launch a social enterprise.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/02/03/founder-bertil-hult-sees-education-first-breaking-down-global-barriers/KK6hpFwDqvocR73w0Xf9jO/story.html Education First aims to bridge barriers with exchange], Boston Globe, 2/4/2013</ref> \n\nThe Prize is a partnership between [[Hult International Business School]] and the [[United Nations Foundation]]. Former U.S. president [[Bill Clinton]] selects the challenge topic and announces the winner each September; he mentioned it in a 2012 ''[[Time]]'' article about \"the top 5 ideas that are changing the world for the better\".<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2125031-6,00.html The case for optimism], ''Time'', 10/1/2012</ref><ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/president-bill-clinton-awards-usd1m-hult-prize-at-united-nations-headquarters-to-four-college-students-from-the-uk-for-innovative-rice-farming-startup--issues-10th-anniversary-youth-challenge-300714747.html Cision - President Bill Clinton Awards USD1M Hult Prize at United Nations Headquarters]</ref> The Hult prize has been referred to as the \u201cNobel Prize for students\u201d by Nobel laureate [[Muhammad Yunus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/07/tackling-cavities-in-indias-slums-with-xylitol-gum/|title=Tackling Cavities in India's Slums with Xylitol Gum|last=Higa|first=Liriel|date=2014-11-07|website=On the Ground|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nA lecture given by [[One Laptop Per Child]] director [[Chuck Kane]] sparked the idea for a business case competition focused on solving global problems via social entrepreneurship. In March 2010, MBA students Ahmad Ashkar, Tamara Sam, Carolin Bachmann, Jose Escobar and Nabil Chaachou, launched the Hult Global Case Challenge, later renamed the Hult Prize.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">[https://www.bloomberg.com/video/creating-the-next-wave-of-social-entrepreneurs-mKQuhLy4QHSokxb1~JOEcQ.html Creating the next wave of social entrepreneurs], Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Bloomberg TV\u2019s Taking Stock with Pimm Fox, 5/30/2013 {{dl|date=March 2020}}</ref> Students from over ninety business schools competed at three Hult campuses in Dubai, London and Boston simultaneously.\n\nIn 2011, the competition expanded into five regional rounds at Hult campuses around the globe (Shanghai, Dubai, London, Boston and San Francisco) with the winning team from each region continuing to the Global Finals in New York City. President Bill Clinton first announced the Hult Prize Winner (still called the Hult Global Case Challenge at the time) in 2011, and has done so in each subsequent year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/eyes-on-prize-ahmad-ashkar-592285.html|title=Eyes on the prize: Ahmad Ashkar|last=King|first=Neil|website=ArabianBusiness.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> In 2012, the competition expanded to include three tracks - energy, housing and education - and the Global Final was held at the New York Public Library. By 2013, the Prize attracted more than 10,000 MBA and undergraduate applicants.<ref>http://video.foxnews.com/v/2421703863001/, Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Fox News, 5/30/2013.</ref>\n\nMany major business schools run internal competitions to pre-qualify teams, which they then send into the competition. In 2018, 115,000 students from over 100 countries participated in the Hult Prize, competing for a total of $5m in prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4318dc28-5a97-11e8-806a-808d194ffb75|title=What does it take to win a business plan competition?|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n\n=== Leadership ===\nAhmad Ashkar has served as Founding CEO of the Hult Prize since 2009.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other members of the current leadership team are Karim Samra (COO), Charlemagne Quinitio (Vice-President, Global Operations and Finance), Nelly Andrade (Global Director, Hult Prize On-Campus Program), Jamal Khayyat (Head of Global Business Development), Callum Porter-Harris (Global Director of Regionals), Ayman Arandi (National Program Director), Ricardo Alvarez (Head of Global Brand & Communications) and Priya Sultan (Global Projects Director).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/about/|title=About|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Programs ===\nSince its launch in 2010, Hult has launched several programs. The original competition is now the Hult Prize Flagship Competition, with other programs being the Hult Prize Regionals, Hult Prize on Campus, the Hult Prize Accelerator and the Hult Prize Summit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/faqs/|title=Frequently Asked Questions|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n== Competitions ==\n\n=== 2010: Early childhood education ===\n[[File:One Laptop Per Child at Holmes Elementary (11292383786).jpg|thumb|Children with laptops from [[One Laptop per Child|One Laptop Per Child]], a non-profit organization and the case study of the 2010 inaugural Hult Global Case Challenge. ]]\nThe inaugural Hult Prize was held as The Global Case Challenge and participants sought ways to support and scale the impact of [[One Laptop per Child|One Laptop Per Child]]'s mission in developing, producing and distributing affordable laptops, particularly for developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2010-challenge/|title=2010 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011: Global water crisis ===\nIn 2011, the Hult competition focused on the topic of clean water. Participants were challenged to provide and improve clean water and sanitation ways for the more than 2.5 billion people worldwide, that don't have access to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2011-challenge/|title=2011 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> The competition was held in partnership with [[Matt Damon]] and [[Water.org]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1760918/can-matt-damon-bring-clean-water-africa|title=Can Matt Damon Bring Clean Water To Africa?|last=Staff|first=Fast Company|date=2011-06-20|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> The prize was awarded to a team from [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]], led by [[Akanksha Hazari]], with their proposal turning into the social enterprise [[m.Paani]], working on digital ways to provide safe water, education, healthcare, energy, nutrition and mobility to rural Indian communities.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessweekly.co.uk/news/academia-research/cambridge-stars-clinton%E2%80%99s-1m-social-challenge|title=Cambridge stars in Clinton\u2019s $1m social challenge {{!}} Business Weekly {{!}} Technology News {{!}} Business news {{!}} Cambridge and the East of England|website=www.businessweekly.co.uk|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012: Housing, education and energy ===\nIn 2012, the Hult competition revolved around global energy poverty, seeking to support the many people worldwide, that still live without electricity. The challenge was focused on removing the use of kerosene lamps in Africa by 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2012-challenge/|title=2012 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> The winner was a group from [[New York University Abu Dhabi]], consisting of international students. The group was priced for their solution to supply solar lighting. To apply the student\u00b4s ideas, [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] [[SolarAid]] was awarded with a part of the prize money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyuad.nyu.edu/en/news/latest-news/honors-and-awards/2012/april/nyuad-team-wins-hult-global-case-challenge.html|title=NYUAD Team Wins Hult Global Case Challenge|last=Dhabi|first=NYU Abu|website=New York University Abu Dhabi|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013: The Global Food Crisis ===\nDue to the fact that nearly one billion people worldwide are still suffering from hunger, the Hult Prize 2013 focused on the Global Food Crisis. The 2013 topic was personally chosen by Bill Clinton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2013-challenge/|title=2013 Challenge|date=2017-03-30|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> The prize went to Aspire Food from [[McGill University]] for the idea of processing edible insects to produce a sustainable source of protein. This way providing slum communities with an easier and better access to essential nutrients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/author/hult-prize-team-mcgill|title=Hult Prize: Team McGill {{!}} HuffPost|website=www.huffpost.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014: Solving Non-Communicable Disease in the Urban Slum ===\nThe 2014 Hult Prize concentrated on Healthcare: Non-Communicable Disease in the Urban Slums. The students were challenged to build sustainable and scalable social enterprises to fight again non-communicable disease in slums.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2014-challenge/|title=2014 Challenge|date=2017-03-29|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The prize was awarded to a group of five alumni from [[Indian School of Business]] (ISB). The winning team, [[NanoHealth|Nano Health]], suggested the education and employment of health workers, who would run screening camps, help to diagnose diseases and support citizens in lifestyle changes. The health workers were equipped with \u201cDoc-in-a-Box\u201d \u2013 a diagnostic tool for basic health indicators. Nano Health is supported from various industrial partners, including GVK Biosciences, who supported with project with their tool HEART (Health Emphasized Analytical and Reporting Tool).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isb.edu/news-media/isb-updates/isb-team-wins-hult-prize-and-usd-1-million-in-prize-money|title=ISB Team wins Hult Prize and USD 1 million in prize money from HULT and Clinton Foundation {{!}} Indian School of Business (ISB)|website=www.isb.edu|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== 2015: Early Childhood Education ===\nIn 2015, the prize challenged teams to find solutions for the early childhood education gap (0-6 years old kids).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2015-challenge/|title=2015 Challenge|date=2017-03-29|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> The winning team was IMPCT from the IMBA Program at [[National Chengchi University]] in [[Taiwan]]. The team developed PlayCare, a micro-equity platform, where everyone can invest in sustainable education businesses under a profit-sharing-model. The education businesses, like care centers in urban slums, supports also with educational efforts and increasing enrollment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://imba.nccu.edu.tw/en/news/IMPCT-Wins-the-2015-Hult-Prize-Finals-84239310|title=IMPCT Wins the 2015 Hult Prize Finals!|website=IMBA, NCCU|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> The team also named [[Ann Louie Li]] their Founding Ambassador, who pioneered  the social media movement 'Creating an #IMPCT'. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ent.abs-cbn.com/pbbseason7/articles-photos/61090517-remember-the-other-half-of-jamli-love-team-heres-a-photo-update-about-ann-li-2492|title=Remember the other half of #JamLi love team? Here's a photo update about Ann Li! {{!}} ABS-CBN Entertainment|website=ent.abs-cbn.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://firstclasse.com.my/rich-heirs-on-instagram-ann-louie-li/|title=Rich Heirs on Instagram: Ann Louie Li, the globetrotting Forbes 30 under 30 multihyphenate|date=2020-02-27|website=FirstClasse|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016: Crowded urban spaces  ===\nThe 2016 Hult Prize challenge for teams participating was to present the idea for a business that would double the income of 1 million people in the developing world by 2022. The prize was awarded to a team from [[Earlham College]] whose business idea, Magic Bus Ticketing, focused on improving the public transportation system in Kenya.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/devinthorpe/2016/10/05/hult-prize-winners-to-deploy-1m-prize-improving-public-transit-in-kenya/|title=Hult Prize Winners To Deploy $1M Prize Improving Public Transit In Kenya|last=Thorpe|first=Devin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\nJudges at the 2016 competition were: [[Mohammed Ashour]], CEO of [[Aspire Food Group]], [[Robert Collymore|Bob Collymore]], CEO of [[Safaricom]], [[Brian Fetherstonhaugh]], Chairman & CEO of OgilvyOne, Kathleen Rogers, President of Earth Day, [[Premal Shah]], President and co-founder of Kiva and [[Muhammad Yunus]], 2006 Nobel Peace Prize recipient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/2017-Hult-Prize-Media-Kit.pdf|title=Hult Prize Media Kit (2017)}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017: Refugees \u2013 Reawakening Human Potential ===\nIn 2017, the Hult competition centered the motion of humanity, and the ensuing massive demographic shifts, which pressure social, political, and physical infrastuctures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/past/2017-challenge/|title=2017 Challenge|date=2017-03-28|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> The Competition was won by TeamEME from [[College of Electrical and Mechanical Engineering|EME College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pakwired.com/hult-prize-competition-2017-teameme-of-nust-wins-to-represent-pakistan-in-regional-finals-in-dubai/|title=Hult Prize Competition 2017 - TeamEME Wins to Represent Pakistan in Regional Finals in Dubai|last=Rasheed|first=Mohsin|date=2017-01-07|website=PakWired - Latest Startup and Technology News from Pakistan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Transform \u2013 Harnessing the Power of Energy ===\nIn 2018, the prize challenged student teams to find and evolve energy innovations to enhance million of lives. The Hult Prize assumes, that it is necessary for the world to find more disruption that taps into energy innovations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hultprize.org/current/2018-challenge/|title=2018 Challenge|date=2017-09-21|website=Hult Prize|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-14}}</ref>  The competition was won by team SunRice from University College London.\n\n*\n\n== Partnerships ==\nIn 2010, the competition focused on education in partnership with One Laptop Per Child.<ref>[http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html Top business school students to compete for innovative solution to educate 2 billion poor kids] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030002208/http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html |date=2010-10-30 }}, Chinastakes.com, 2/25/2010</ref> The 2011 event partnered with [[water.org]] to focus on the provision of clean water.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8c9679f4-f0b0-11df-8cc5-00144feab49a.html Matt Damon\u2019s charity benefits from global MBA advice], Financial Times, 11/15/2010</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n[https://rajmarga.com/hult-prize-at-iost-tribhuvan-university/ Hult Prize At IOST, Tribhuvan University]- Rajmarga.com\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news|last1=Mazzoni|first1=Mary|title=The Hult Prize: Incubating for Impact|url=http://www.triplepundit.com/2016/11/ahmad-ashkar-hult-prize-describes-company-future/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=Triple Pundit|date=8 November 2016}}\n\n* {{cite news|last1=Melby|first1=Caleb|title=Hult Global Case Challenge Is Changing The Social Business Paradigm|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/calebmelby/2012/04/30/hult-global-case-challenge-is-changing-the-social-business-paradigm/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=Forbes|date=30 April 2012}}\n\n* {{cite news|last1=Woodward|first1=Vivienne|title=The $1 Million \"Nobel Prize\" For Social Entrepreneurs Now Dedicated To Refugees|url=https://money.good.is/articles/hult-prize-refugee-aid|accessdate=11 April 2017|publisher=GOOD Money|date=7 April 2017}}\n\n* {{cite news|last1=Bahree|first1=Megha|title=A million dollars to solve the world's problems|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2015/01/11/ozy-million-dollars-solve-world-problems/21501745/|accessdate=9 April 2017|agency=USA Today|date=11 January 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.hultprize.org/ Official website]\n\n{{Hult}}\n\n[[Category:Competitions]]\n[[Category:Social entrepreneurship]]\n[[Category:Competitions by country]]\n[[Category:Competitions in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: ''Time'' \u2192 ''Time'',typo(s) fixed: USD  \u2192 US$, infrastuctures \u2192 infrastructures, \u00b4s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hult_Prize"}
{"title_page": "Gordes", "text_new": "{{For|the town and district in the Aegean region of Turkey|G\u00f6rdes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Expand French|topic=geo|date=March 2016|Gordes}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name               = Gordes\n|commune status     = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image              = 1 gordes pano 2016.jpg\n|caption            = \n|image coat of arms = Blason Gordes 84.svg\n|arrondissement     = Apt\n|canton             = Apt\n|INSEE              = 84050\n|postal code        = 84220\n|mayor              = Maurice Chabert\n|term               = 1995\u20132008\n|intercommunality   = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|43.9119|5.2008|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation min m    = 111\n|elevation m        = 373\n|elevation max m    = 635\n|area km2           = 48.04\n|population         = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date    = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}\n\n'''Gordes''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Vaucluse]] d\u00e9partement in the [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]] [[Regions of France|region]] in southeastern France. The residents are known as ''Gordiens.'' The nearest big city is [[Avignon]]; smaller cities nearby include [[Cavaillon]], [[L'Isle-sur-la-Sorgue]] and [[Apt, Vaucluse|Apt]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe territory of Gordes occupies some of \"[[Vaucluse Mountains|Les Monts de Vaucluse]]\", a group of mountains and hills, part in the valley of the Calavon (a local river) also called the \"Luberon Valley\".\n\n=== Access ===\nThe main access to the village of Gordes is the departmental road D2 then the departmental road  D15, coming from [[Cavaillon]]. It is from the latter road, below the Bel-Air rock, that you can observe the most famous and photographed point of view of the village.\n\nGordes is located 38 kilometres east from [[Avignon]] and its TGV station, 75 kilometres from the Marseille Provence international airport and 87 kilometres from Marseille. The closest \"gares SNCF\" (normal train station) are located in L'Isle-sur-la-Sorgue and Cavaillon.\n\n===Neighboring communes===\nNeighboring villages are [[Venasque]] and [[Murs, Vaucluse|Murs]] to the north, [[Joucas]] and [[Roussillon (Vaucluse)|Roussillon]] to the east, [[Goult]], [[Saint-Pantal\u00e9on (Vaucluse)|Saint-Pantal\u00e9on]], [[Beaumettes]] and [[Opp\u00e8de]] to the south and [[Cabri\u00e8res-d'Avignon]] and [[Saumane-de-Vaucluse]] to the west.\n\n=== Topography ===\nLocated between two geographic area, Gordes is one of the biggest [[Communes of France|communes]] of the area with 4,804 hectares. The north is defined by the southern edge of the [[Vaucluse Mountains]]. The highest point of the commune (635 meters) is in this area, next to ''la Pouraque''  and ''les Trois Termes''. The south of the commune is made by the Calavon valley, also called the Luberon Valley, and a few hills in the area. The lowest height of the commune, at 111 meters, is in the south in the area called ''plan de l'Alba''.\n\nThe village itself is located in the center of the commune, on a giant calcareous rock from the Vaucluse Mountains, dominating the valley.\n\n=== Geology ===\nWith a wide variation of the land, geology of the commune is divided into several distinct zones.\n\nIn the north, on the [[Vaucluse Mountains]], are soils dating mainly from Upper Jurassic with urgonian limestone and calcareous clay. There are also, in very low amounts and primarily localized over the Senanque Abbey, soils dating from the Eocene / Oligocene, composed of limestone, sand, and clay.\n\nGeology in the south of the village is more complex. The plain in Gordes (southeast) is composed of soil dating from the Quaternary (fluvial deposits, colluvium and scree) and soils of the Late Jurassic period (calcareous clay and blue marl). The hills area of \"les garrigues\" (in the south) is composed of soil dating from the Cretaceous \u2013 Paleocene period (calcareous sandstone, calcareous lacustrine clay, colorful, white and ocher sands and some ferruginous) and from the Miocene period (molasses limestone, sand and marl). Finally, the soil of the territory down to the plain of Calavon with some slightly higher ground dating from the Miocene and one lower from the Quaternary.\n\n===Climate===\nGordes has a Mediterranean climate characterised by relatively dry summers and cool, damp winters. The city is often subject to windy weather; the strongest wind is the [[mistral (wind)|mistral]].\n\nIn summer, high temperatures associated with a reduced amount of rain creates a drought of almost one or two months a year according to the \"Gaussen index\" (temperatures in Celsius degrees twice higher than rains in millimeters).<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.atlas-parcduluberon.com/atlas/images/EnSavoirPlus_survol.gif Atlas du parc du Luberon]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe name \"Gordes\" derives from the [[Celtic languages|Celtic word]] \"Vordense\". Vordense was pronounced ''Gordenses'',  then ''Gordae/Gordone'', and finally ''G\u00f2rda'' then translated into French \"Gordes\".<ref>''GORDES notes d'histoire'' by Jean-Louis Morand page 9.</ref>\n\n=== Early history ===\nOccupation by the Roman empire.<ref>''GORDES notes d'histoire'' by Jean-Louis Morand page 17 to 24 / \"L'\u00e9poque romaine\".</ref> The area is full of evidence of their occupation especially the Roman road passing through Apt and Carpentras and crossing the valley.  Gallo-Roman remains were found in \"Bouisses\" district (skeletons, amphorae, columns) or Gallo-Roman substructures in the hamlet of \"les Gros\".\n\n[[Image:Castle of Gordes by JM Rosier.JPG|thumb|The view from north of the castle shows the ancient and the Renaissance parts.]]\n\n=== Middle Ages and Renaissance ===\nIn the 8th century, a [[Benedictine]] abbey known as [[Saint-Chaffret]] was founded by monks of the Abbey of Saint-Chaffre in [[Monastier-en-Velay]] on the site of an ancient ''cella'' (Roman temple) destroyed during the [[Arab]] invasions.<ref>''GORDES notes d'histoire'' by Jean-Louis Morand page 39 to 53, \"''Histoire de Saint Chaffret''\"</ref>\n\nIn 1031, a castle was built and the Latin word [[castra|\"castrum\"]] was added to what thus became \"Castrum Gordone\". The castle was re-enforced in 1123 to become a \"''nobile castrum''\", the only one known among the many castles nearby.<ref>''GORDES notes d'histoire'' by Jean-Louis Morand page 249 to 253 \"Le ch\u00e2teau de Gordes\" then page 205 to 216 / \"G\u00e9n\u00e9alogie des familles\".</ref>\n\nIn 1148 the [[S\u00e9nanque Abbey]] was established under the patronage of Alfant, [[Bishop of Cavaillon]], and [[Ramon Berenguer II, Count of Barcelona]], [[Count of Provence]], by Cistercian monks who came from [[Mazan Abbey]] in the [[Ard\u00e8che]].\n\nAfter the death of King Ren\u00e9 of Provence, the territory of Provence was incorporated in 1481 into the kingdom of France as a \"province royale fran\u00e7aise\" (French royal province). An insurrection broke out in the former states of Agoult-Simiane and County of Forcalquier. Gordes is distinguished by a strong opposition to French centralism but will pay heavily for its claims of independence. A year later, with the wedding of his son, Jacques Raybaud de Simiane takes the title of \"Baron de Gordes\".\n\n=== Second World War ===\nDuring World War II, Gordes was an active resistance village and was later awarded a medal, the [[Croix de guerre 1939-1945 (France)|Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945]].\n\nOn 21 August 1944, almost a week after the beginning of the [[Operation Dragoon]] on the Proven\u00e7al coast, a German patrol was attacked by the resistance. The day after, 22 August, the village was subject to violent reprisals. The Germans forced the inhabitants to enter their homes, shooting those who were late or that were not cooperating, and started to shoot from the rock on the other side with a canon and destroyed a dozen houses. On the other side of the village, the rest of the troops set fire to a chariot, pieces of wood and houses, blocking potential followers. More than twenty houses were destroyed. After the Liberation the resistance destroyed another part of the village, including the notarial house with all the archives. All this destruction brought the municipality the sad privilege to appear amongst three \"stricken cities\" of the Vaucluse department. By war's end, thirteen persons had been killed or executed in Gordes, twenty inhabitants had been shot by the enemy and five inhabitants were deported.\n\n=== After World War II ===\nAfter a period of reconstruction, the village started to attract artists like [[Marc Chagall]] or [[Jean Deyrolle]] who discovered the village in 1947 and will in turn attract artist friends such as [[Serge Poliakoff]], [[Victor Vasarely|Vasarely]], [[Jean Dewasne|Dewasne]], etc.\n\n===Armory===\nThe primary ones are reported in 1696 in the [[Armorial G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de France]] and coming from the Gordes-Simiane family.\n\n{{Blazon-arms\n| img1=Blason famille Gordes.svg\n| legend1=Arms of the Gordes family\n| text=The arms of the Gordes family are [[blazon]]ed :<br /> \"de gueules \u00e0 une gourde d'or\". \n}}\n\n{{Blazon-arms\n| img1=Blason famille Simiane.svg\n| legend1=Arms of the Simiane family\n| text=The arms of the Simiane family are [[blazon]]ed :<br />\"d'or sem\u00e9 altern\u00e9 de tours et de fleurs de lys d'azur\".\n}}\n\n{{Blazon-arms\n| img1=Blason Gordes 84.svg\n| legend1=1984's armory\n| text=In 1984, new arms are created : \"Mantel\u00e9 d'or \u00e0 deux gourdes de gueules, et de gueules \u00e0 une gourde d'or\".\n\n<br />\nThe design is clearly based on the Gordes family armory in terms of colors and form.\n}}\n\n=== Other historical language names ===\n{{Lang-oc|G\u00f2rda}} in classical norm of provencal, {{Lang|oc|Gordo}} in Mistralian norm\n\n== Administration ==\n[[File:Hotel simiane in Gordes by JM Rosier.jpg|thumb|The \"Hotel Simiane\", historical building with the new town office.]]\n\nThe commune of Gordes has numerous infrastructures of public utility like the \"gendarmerie\", the fire brigade, the post office, a tax office, a library, etc.\n\n===Sister cities===\n* {{Flagicon|France}} [[Annet-sur-Marne]], France, since 1985.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [[:fr:Fichier:Jumelage Gordes Annet-sur-Marnes bulletin municipal 1986.jpg|Article from the \"bulletin municipal\" of Gordes, 1986.]]</ref>\n\n=== Fiscality ===\n{| align=\"center\" rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"border: 1px solid #999; border-right: 2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background: #FFFFFF\"\n|+ style=\"font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em\"|Taxation of households and businesses in Gordes in 2009<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.taxe.com/index-impots-departement-commune~84050.html local taxes, Gordes]</ref> \n|-style=\"background: #adcdf1\"\n! Tax !!Communal part!! Intercomunal part !!Part for the department!! Part for region\n|-\n| Housing tax || align=center|6.56 % || align=center|0.00 % || align=center|7.55 % || align=center|0.00 % \n|-\n| Property tax on built properties || align=center|9.83 % || align=center|0.00 % || align=center|10.20 % || align=center|2.36 % \n|-\n| Property tax on non-built properties ||  align=center|38.51 %  || align=center|0.00 % ||align=center|28.96 % || align=center|8.85 % \n|-\n| Business Tax || align=center|00.00 % ||align=center|19.99 % || align=center|13.00 % || align=center|3.84 % \n|}\n\n== Demographics ==\n<center>\n<timeline>\nColors=\n  id:lightgrey value:gray(0.9)\n  id:darkgrey  value:gray(0.7)\n  id:sfondo value:rgb(1,1,1)\n  id:barra value:rgb(0.6,0.7,0.8)\n\nImageSize  = width:850 height:350\nPlotArea   = left:50 bottom:50 top:30 right:30\nDateFormat = x.y\nPeriod     = from:0 till:3100\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical\nAlignBars  = justify\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:darkgrey increme