{"title_page": "Castlevania (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American adult animated series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Castlevania\n| image                    = Castlevania netflix titlecard.png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]<br />[[Dark fantasy]]<br />[[Action film|Action]]<br />[[Adventure film|Adventure]]<br />[[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n| developer                = [[Adi Shankar]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Castlevania]]''|[[Konami]]}}\n| writer                   = [[Warren Ellis]]\n| director                 = {{plainlist|\n* Sam Deats\n* Adam Deats\n* Spencer Wan\n}}\n| voices                   = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list --> {{plainlist|\n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]\n* [[James Callis]]\n* [[Graham McTavish]]\n* Alejandra Reynoso\n* [[Tony Amendola]]\n* [[Matt Frewer]]\n* [[Emily Swallow]]\n* [[Theo James]]\n* [[Adetokumboh M'Cormack]]\n* [[Jaime Murray]]\n* [[Peter Stormare]]\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Trevor Morris (musician)|Trevor Morris]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 3<!-- Increment when new seasons/series begin. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| num_episodes             = 22<!-- Value is incremented when new episodes air. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{unbulleted list|[[Adi Shankar]]|[[Fred Seibert]]|Ted Biaselli|Kevin Kolde|[[Larry Tanz]]|Warren Ellis}}\n| producer                 = Toshiyuki Hiruma<br/>Maki Terashima<br/>Brad Graeber<br />Jason Williams\n| runtime                  = 23\u201331 minutes\n| company                  = {{unbulleted list|[[Frederator Studios]]|[[Powerhouse Animation Studios]]|Shankar Animation|Project 51 Productions|Mua Film}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n| network                  = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| related                  = [[Bootleg Multiverse]]\n| website                  = <!-- Remove or comment out this parameter line completely if URL exists on or is moved to Wikidata -->\n| production_website       = \n}}\n'''''Castlevania''''' is an American [[Adult animation|adult animated]] [[web television|web]] [[television series]] based on the Japanese video game series [[Castlevania|of the same name]] by [[Konami]]. The first two seasons adapt the 1989 entry ''[[Castlevania III: Dracula's Curse]]'' and follow [[Trevor Belmont]], [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Alucard]] and [[Sypha Belnades]] as they defend the nation of [[Wallachia]] from [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Dracula]] and his minions. Seasons 2 and 3 borrow characters and elements from the 2005 entry ''[[Castlevania: Curse of Darkness]]''.\n\nThe series was originally planned as a film, developed by producer Kevin Kolde and his company Project 51. Kolde had a contract for a script with writer [[Warren Ellis]] in 2007; the project entered [[development hell]] until about 2015, when [[Adi Shankar]] boarded the project and it was picked up by streaming service [[Netflix]]. [[Powerhouse Animation Studios]] joined the team and production commenced. Its art style is heavily influenced by Japanese [[anime]] and [[Ayami Kojima]]'s artwork in ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]'' with the production team including staff members who worked in the Japanese anime industry.\n\nThe series premiered on Netflix on July 7, 2017, and was renewed for an expanded second season of eight episodes on the same day; the second season premiered on October 26, 2018. A ten-episode third season was greenlit by Netflix and released on March 5, 2020. On March 27, 2020, Netflix announced they have renewed the series for a fourth season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2020/03/27/castlevania-season-4-netflix/|title=Netflix Announces Castlevania Season 4|website=Anime|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nWhen his wife is burned at the stake after being falsely accused of witchcraft, the vampire Count [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Dracula]] declares all the people of [[Wallachia]] will pay with their lives. He summons an army of demons which overruns the country, causing the people to live lives of fear and distrust. To combat this, the outcast monster hunter [[Trevor Belmont]] takes up arms against Dracula's forces, aided by the [[magician (fantasy)|magician]] [[Sypha Belnades]] and Dracula's [[dhampir]] son [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Alucard]].\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{further|List of Castlevania characters}}\n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] as [[Trevor Belmont]], the last living member of the Belmont clan, an excommunicated family of monster hunters.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/castlevania-animated-netflix-cast-graham-mctavish/|title=Netflix 'Castlevania' Voice Cast Includes 'Preacher,' 'Hannibal' Alum|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Kevin|date=June 28, 2017|website=Screen Crush|accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[James Callis]] as [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Adrian Alucard Tepes]], the [[dhampir]] son of Dracula and Lisa Tepes, who seeks to protect humanity from his father.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Graham McTavish]] as [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Vlad Dracula Tepes]], a vampire who swears vengeance on humanity for the death of his wife Lisa, summoning an army of monsters to destroy all the people of Wallachia. (season 1 - 2)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* Alejandra Reynoso as [[Sypha Belnades]], a Speaker and the Elder's granddaughter who wields powerful magic.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Tony Amendola]] as The Elder, the leader of a group of Speakers aiding the people of Gresit whom Trevor befriends.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" /> (season 1)\n* [[Matt Frewer]] as The Bishop, a psychotic clergyman who orders the burning of Lisa Tepes for witchcraft, later being named the bishop of Gresit. (season 1)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Emily Swallow]] as [[Lisa (Castlevania)|Lisa Tepes]], Dracula's beloved wife who is burned at the stake after being falsely accused of witchcraft. (season 1)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Theo James]] as [[Hector (Castlevania)|Hector]], a devil forgemaster called upon to serve Dracula in his war against humanity. He has a hatred of humanity, but his na\u00efvet\u00e9 makes him easy to deceive or manipulate.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/castlevania-season-2-voice-cast-characters/|title=Castlevania Season 2 Voice Cast and Character Guide|last=Donaldson|first=Kayleigh|date=October 26, 2018|website=Screen Rant|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Adetokumboh M'Cormack]] as [[Isaac (Castlevania)|Isaac]], a rivalrous devil forgemaster and fierce loyalist of Dracula who helps to lead his army.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Jaime Murray]] as [[Carmilla (Castlevania)|Carmilla]], a scheming vampire mistress and member of Dracula's war council who seeks to usurp him.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Peter Stormare]] as Godbrand, a viking vampire warlord called upon to serve Dracula in the battle against Wallachia.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2)\n* [[Jessica Brown Findlay]] as Lenore, the diplomat member of the Council of Sisters. She is in charge of subduing Hector. (season 3)\n* [[Yasmine Al Massri]] as Morana, the strategist member of the Council of Sisters. (season 3)\n* [[Ivana Milicevic]] as Striga, the military member of the Council of Sisters. (season 3)\n* [[Bill Nighy]] as [[List of Castlevania characters#Saint Germain|Saint Germain]], a strange man investigating the priory of Lindenfeld. (season 3)\n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Sala, the leader of the monks of Lindenfeld who actually seeks to resurrect Dracula. (season 3)\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as The Judge, the town leader of Lindenfeld who wishes to keep peace and order in town. (season 3)\n* Toru Uchikado as Taka, a vampire hunter from Japan using a bow. (season 3)\n* [[Rila Fukushima]] as Sumi, a vampire hunter from Japan using a sword. (season 3)\n* [[Barbara Steele]] as Miranda, an old woman possessing magic powers who helps Isaac. (season 3)\n* [[Lance Reddick]] as The Captain, a pirate captain who befriends and helps Isaac. (season 3)\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| released    = y\n| allreleased = y\n\n| color1      = #420701\n| link1       = #Season 1 (2017)\n| episodes1   = 4\n| start1      = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n\n| color2      = #770101\n| link2       = #Season 2 (2018)\n| episodes2   = 8\n| start2      = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n\n| color3      = #5F5149\n| link3       = #Season 3 (2020)\n| episodes3   = 10\n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2017)===\n{{Episode table |background=#420701 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Witchbottle\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = In [[Wallachia]] in 1455, a young woman named [[List of Castlevania characters#Lisa|Lisa]] who wishes to be a doctor seeks out [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Vlad Dracula Tepes]], a vampire with advanced scientific knowledge. Intrigued by her courage and ambition, Dracula agrees to teach her, while she in turn offers to help him reconnect with humanity. The two eventually fall in love and marry. Twenty years later (1475), in the town of [[T\u00e2rgovi\u0219te]], Lisa is burned at the stake after a bishop discovers scientific equipment in her home and accuses her of witchcraft. Dracula is devastated and furious upon learning of his wife's death and declares the people have one year to make their peace, after which every human in Wallachia will die by his hand. His son [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Adrian]] tells him to instead go after the man responsible instead of all of humanity, but Dracula refuses to listen and attacks him. One year later, the archbishop hosts a celebration in defiance of Dracula. As promised, Dracula kills the archbishop, destroys the church and orders his demon army to kill every person left in Wallachia. As the army spreads across the land, the people place the blame on the kingdom's noble families, including the Belmonts.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Necropolis\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Following an altercation at a pub, [[Trevor Belmont]] seeks food and respite in the city of Gresit, which has been besieged by Dracula's forces every night. As he passes through town, he learns that the townspeople blame a group of magic users known as the Speakers for Dracula's assault. He saves their Elder from a pair of corrupt priests, who brings him back to his home to meet his fellow Speakers. Trevor insists they leave the city for their own safety, but the Elder refuses, as his grandchild has gone missing after venturing into the catacombs below the city in search of the \"sleeping soldier\", a legendary hero who they believe can defeat Dracula. Begrudgingly, Trevor agrees to retrieve the missing grandchild.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Labyrinth\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Exploring the catacombs, Trevor realizes that they have been unusually constructed and contain devices matching old family descriptions of devices within Dracula's castle. Finding a stone statue in the visage of a Speaker, Trevor is attacked by a giant cyclops. He defeats the creature, releasing its curse, and rescues the Elder's grandchild, [[Sypha Belnades]]. After returning Sypha to her grandfather, Trevor is summoned to the church by the local bishop, the same bishop who ordered Lisa's execution. He orders Trevor to leave Gresit before sundown, as they plan to lead a mob to kill the Speakers, offering to spare Trevor and restore his family name in exchange. With the Speakers refusing to retreat, Trevor has them hidden in the cyclops' chamber and takes on the priests leading the mob before escaping into the city.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Monument\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Night falls as Dracula's army descends upon Gresit, killing the bishop. As Trevor continues his escape, Sypha appears to aid him, revealing herself as a powerful magic user. Trevor exposes the clergy's actions as the true reason for Dracula's invasion and assists the people in mounting a defense against the demons. During the battle, the floor crumbles beneath Trevor and Sypha and they fall deep into the submerged catacombs of the city. Making their way in deeper, they find the \"sleeping soldier\", revealed to be Adrian, who has spent a year healing from his last fight with Dracula. Adrian, now going by Alucard, engages Trevor in battle, but after seeing his and Sypha's resolve, Alucard relents and reveals that he was testing their abilities because the myth of the \"sleeping soldier\" was actually from the future and foretold Alucard's meeting with Belmont and Sypha. The three prepare to challenge Dracula and end the conflict for good.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2 (2018)===\n{{Episode table |background=#770101 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = War Council\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = A flashback depicts Lisa's home in [[Cerg\u0103u|Lupu]] being raided by the Bishop and his men while Dracula is away, resulting in her arrest to be tried before an inquisition. In the present, Dracula assembles his war council, made up of vampire overlords from across the world, and places human necromancers Hector and Isaac in charge of the war on humanity. The viking vampire Godbrand objects, believing they should rely on vampires instead of humans for leadership, but Dracula believes Hector and Isaac's hatred of their own kind makes them more trustworthy. As Gresit rebuilds after the battle, Sypha and Trevor see off the other Speakers while Alucard comes to terms with the decision to kill his father. At the castle, Godbrand laments to Hector that their war is being fought with no strategy apart from wanton destruction. Hector implies that Dracula wants all humans dead no matter the methods used, to Godbrand's disappointment. Dracula teleports the castle to a different location.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Old Homes\n |DirectedBy      = Spencer Wan\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor and Sypha reunite with Alucard and ask how to locate Dracula's castle when it can move from place to place. Trevor recommends revisiting his old family estate, as the hold beneath the ruins contains plenty of information and tools for monster-hunting. At Dracula's castle, the vampire mistress Carmilla arrives and causes further discord among the council by criticizing Dracula's approach and inquiring his reasons of having not sired Lisa into a vampire. While traveling to the Belmont estate, Trevor's party is attacked by Dracula's forces; the group slays all the attackers, save one injured demon who escapes. At the castle, Isaac reminisces on his past, having killed his previous abusive master in a moment that shaped his ideals. Godbrand brings Isaac the injured demon, now dead, to extract information from it with his necromancy. At another assembly, the generals argue whether to continue their attack on [[Arge\u0219 County|Arge\u0219]] or move the siege towards [[Br\u0103ila County|Br\u0103ila]] at Carmilla's suggestion. Isaac informs everyone of his findings, believing Alucard is working with a Belmont. Carmilla urges Dracula to keep watch on the Belmont estate, believing it may contain something that could destroy them.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Shadow Battles\n |DirectedBy      = Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Carmilla tries to convince Hector to create creatures to send to the Belmont house while encouraging Dracula to select Br\u0103ila as their next target. Hector reminisces on how Dracula found him in the east of [[Rhodes]] and recruited him to raise an army, though Hector asked for a humane cull of humans rather than a cruel genocide. Trevor, Sypha and Alucard reach the ruins of the Belmont estate and open a magically-sealed door leading to a massive underground library. Sypha begins researching and Trevor locates several monster-hunting weapons, including the Morning Star whip, while Alucard is left uneasy by the various vampire remains preserved there. At Dracula's castle, Godbrand expresses his dissatisfaction with the plan to exterminate the human race, believing they will be left hungry without human blood to consume, and Dracula rebukes him. Carmilla tells Godbrand that Dracula must take the castle to Br\u0103ila, revealing how she killed the vampire who sired her after he became old and mad, deeming Dracula has become the same and unfit to lead them.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Broken Mast\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Godbrand comes to agree with Carmilla that Dracula is not fit to lead and something must be done to change his plans. At the Belmont library, Trevor discovers a magical mirror which allows them to see things far away, and he bonds with Sypha. Carmilla continues to try to recruit Hector, intending to unseat Dracula if the castle is moved to Br\u0103ila. In a flashback, Isaac recalls how Dracula saved his life and recruited him to create his army. Godbrand and the other vampire generals grow tired of living without human blood and set out on demonic horses to a nearby village, slaughtering the people. Dracula speaks to Isaac about the war hall turning against him and confesses he lied to Hector about his intent to spare a few humans. Godbrand privately approaches Isaac and suggests that they should pursue the war without Dracula, Isaac killing Godbrand for his treasonous intentions.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Last Spell\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Isaac releases Godbrand's ashes from the castle rooftop while Carmilla commands her troops to assemble at Br\u0103ila. Hector convinces Isaac to agree to the attack on Br\u0103ila. Hector feeds this back to Carmilla and informs her that his night creatures have nearly reached the Belmont estate. Isaac discusses Hector's request with Dracula, but asserts that there is no betrayal to be concerned about. Dracula reminisces about a time he once savored killing humans but admits he is tired and cares only for results instead of the details. Carmilla and Hector approach Dracula and he approves the attack on Br\u0103ila. Afterwards, Carmilla turns on Hector, explaining he is now implicated in her impending betrayal of Dracula and cannot turn back on her plan now. At the Belmont library, Sypha discovers an unfinished locking spell that could be used to trap the castle in one place. The library starts to shake as Hector's night creatures arrive and attempt to break in.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = The River\n |DirectedBy      = Spencer Wan\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor fights off the demons as Alucard uses the distance mirror to locate Dracula's castle so Sypha can attempt to complete the locking spell. Dracula moves the castle to Br\u0103ila, and most of the vampire generals lead troops across the bridge to attack the town. At Carmilla's behest, Hector reanimates the Bishop and makes him bless the river. Carmilla's troops reveal themselves and bring down the bridge, dropping many of Dracula's soldiers to be destroyed by the now-holy water. Dracula's remaining forces retreat to the castle whilst Carmilla's soldiers cross the river on makeshift bridges. The two armies begin to battle in the castle's main hall, while Carmilla and Hector move elsewhere. Sypha finishes the spell just as Trevor defeats the last of the demons, her struggle against the castle's mechanisms causing the castle to teleport within Br\u0103ila, landing in the river with most of the vampires of both factions killed by the holy water flooding into the castle. Sypha succeeds, disabling the castle's mechanisms while relocating it above the Belmont library.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n |Title           = For Love\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Emerging from the library, Trevor, Sypha and Alucard storm the castle and defeat the remaining vampires in the main hall. Dracula retreats to his study with Isaac, whom he sends through his magic mirror back to the desert to save the human from sacrificing himself to defend Dracula from death. Alucard reaches the study and attacks Dracula, backed by Trevor and Sypha. The group manages to inflict some damage, but Dracula overpowers them, and engages in hand-to-hand combat with Alucard, moving through the castle as they battle. Eventually the two end up in Alucard's childhood room where Dracula has a break down upon realizing the reality of him trying to kill his own son. Dracula allows Alucard to stake him through the heart, while Trevor arrives to decapitate the decomposing vampire and Sypha burns the remains, leaving only his wedding ring intact. Alucard is upset about having killed his father, but Trevor and Sypha reassure him it was the right thing to do as they all walk out of the castle as morning dawns.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n |Title           = End Times\n |DirectedBy      = Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alucard intends to make Dracula's now-deserted castle his grave, but Trevor gifts him the Belmont library along with encouragement to protect both their ancestral homes while using their collective knowledge to help people. Meanwhile, Isaac murders a group of raiders and turns them into the first of his personal army. In Br\u0103ila, Carmilla decides to return to [[Styria]], enslaving Hector for his skills to quickly rebuild her forces and take advantage of the power vacuum left by Dracula's demise. Sypha convinces Trevor to stay with her and join her on new adventures battling monsters, and they bid farewell to Alucard and set off to find the Speakers. Left alone in the castle, Alucard reflects on the loss of his family and is overcome by grief. \n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 3 (2020)===\n{{Episode table |background=#5F5149 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Bless Your Dead Little Hearts\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = A month after Dracula\u2019s death, Alucard tries to adjust to his loneliness, but he misses Trevor and Sypha. Meanwhile, Trevor and Sypha arrive in the small town of Lindenfield, where a local priory sympathizes with Dracula\u2019s cause and wish to punish those responsible for his death. Carmilla returns to her castle in Styria with Hector to reunite with her Council of Sisters (consisting of herself, Lenore, Striga and Morana). Hector is then imprisoned in her castle.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = The Reparation of My Heart\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Somewhere in Northern Africa, Isaac is set on exacting revenge on Hector. He acquires a distance mirror, a magical device which reveals Hector's whereabouts. Isaac and his creatures then depart for Genoa on a boat belonging to a man known as the Captain. In Styria, Carmilla shares her plans to dominate an area of Eastern Europe, effectively enclosing it into a personal pen with humans as livestock. However, when Striga points out how Hector will refuse to forge new demons, Lenore volunteers to convince him otherwise. In Lindenfield, Trevor meets the mysterious Saint Germain, who recognizes him as a Belmont. Germain persuades the priory leader, Sala, to grant him access into the priory. At the Belmont Hold, Alucard is visited by a pair of vampire hunters from Japan, Taka and Sumi.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Investigators\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Befriending the Judge of Lindenfield, Trevor and Sypha learn how one how Dracula's creatures, the Visitor, escaped to the priory and began communicating with the monks. Since then, Sala began refusing townfolk into the priory\u2019s hall and allowed disturbed strangers into the monastery. On the open seas, the Captain and Isaac are debating the merits of humanity. When Isaac says he wishes to continue Dracula's ambitions, his faith is shaken when the Captain challenges him to use his skills to teach humanity how to be kinder. At Carmilla\u2019s castle, Lenore brings food to an unclothed and battered Hector. Wary of her intentions, he attempts to escape, only to be beaten down by Lenore.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = I Have a Scheme\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = At Dracula\u2019s castle, Alucard learns from Taka and Sumi they were once enslaved by one of Dracula's council members, Ch\u014d. Although Ch\u014d died in the previous season finale, Taka and Sumi know another vampire will one day succeed her, and ask Alucard to teach them. Meanwhile, in Styria, relations between Hector and Lenore begin to thaw after she provides him with shoes. At the Lindenfield monastery, Saint Germain is suspicious of the monks, questioning their loyalty to God. He\u2019s fascinated by the symbol on Sala\u2019s armband (the alchemical sign for sulfur used by philosophers to denote Hell). \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 17\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = A Seat of Civilisation and Refinement\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor and the Judge notice alchemical signs have been carved throughout the town by the monks. Outside the monastery, Saint Germain meets Sypha, who knows he is a magician. Joined with Trevor, Saint Germain tells them that he\u2019s in search of a portal to \u201cthe Infinite Corridor\u201d, where he once lost someone dear to him, and that he\u2019s found one beneath the priory. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 18\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = The Good Dream\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats & Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Lenore takes a now clothed Hector with a collar on his neck around Carmilla's castle, and he gradually starts to fall for her charms. In Lindenfield, Germain has a nightmare of falling through the Infinite Corridor, an endless pit of dimensions where he witnesses worlds with giant monsters and spaceships. Before waking up, a woman throws him a crystal which he catches in his hand.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 19\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n |Title           = Worse Things Than Betrayal\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alucard trains Sumi and Taka and takes them to the Belmont Hold, teaching them to start by learning something simple. Returning to the prior in Lindenfield, Saint Germain discovers a book which shows how to bring back the dead from Hell. He heads towards the basement, where he finds the Visitor impaled to the walls. During a two week march from Styria, Issac meets a blind woman, Miranda, who reveals a nearby city houses a Magician who populates it with his own slaves. She tells him the Magician owns a transmission mirror, which can transport Isaac and his army to Styria.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 20\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n |Title           = What the Night Brings\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Saint Germain meets up with Trevor, Sypha and the Judge. They come up with a plan to fight the mad monks and also help Saint Germain open the Infinite Corridor. In the Belmont hold, Alucard bonds with Taka and Sumi during their training, but they are both getting the feeling that Alucard is hiding something from them. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 21\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n |Title           = The Harvest\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats & Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = At sundown, the houses of Lindenfeld that bear the ominous carvings suddenly combust into flames. A battle between the monks and the Judge's men begins, as countless monsters emerge from the Priory. Trevor, Sypha and Saint Germain enter the Priory, while the Visitor opens a portal to Hell where Dracula is seen holding his wife, Lisa. In Styria, Lenores tricks Hector by slipping a magic ring onto his finger as they having sex, which enslaves him. Isaac enter the city and his night creatures successfully defeat the Magician and his Legion, an amalgamation of countless human bodies. As Alucard lies awake at night in Dracula's castle, Taka and Sumi enter the room and proceed to have sex with him, but they then suddenly restrain Alucard by using a trap. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 22\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n |Title           = Abandon All Hope\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Taka and Sumi accuse Alucard of witholding his knowledge of magic from them and not teaching them how to operate the castle. Before they can stake him, he uses his sword to slit their throats. Following their betrayal, Alucard is later seen prostate and weeping on the floor. In thepPriory's basement, Trevor and Sypha battle the monsters while Saint Germain tries closing the portal. Sala stabs the Judge, who suddenly tells Sala about a secret path where he can make his escape. As Trevor destroys the Visitor, Saint Germain closes the corridor with him inside, thanking Trevor and Sypha for their help. Later, Trevor and Sypha find Sala dead in a pit of spikes, with countless human bones. They discover the Judge had been killing children and taking their shoes as trophies to his house. After burning it down, they leave Lindenfeld. At Carmilla\u2019s castle, the sisters have perfected their plan, and Lenore presents them with rings she had forged to make Hector's night creatures loyal to them. The ring will also instantly kill Hector if he attempts to run away from them. Having been manipulated, Hector is distraught at Lenore. The episode ends with Alucard at the castle's entrance, where he has left the impaled bodies of Sumi and Taka as a warning to future visitors. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Warren_Ellis_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg|thumb|175px|[[Warren Ellis]] wrote the series as a direct-to-video film before adapting it for a television format.]]\nIn March 2007, [[Frederator Studios]] acquired the rights to produce an animated film adaption of ''[[Castlevania III: Dracula's Curse]]'', intended as a [[direct-to-video]] production. Frederator brought writer [[Warren Ellis]] aboard as the screenwriter for the series. In an interview with ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'', Warren Ellis said that when he was contacted about ''Castlevania'' he had no previous knowledge of the series and discovered it was a \"Japanese transposition of the [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Horror films]] I grew up with and loved\".<ref name=\"paste magazine\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/07/warren-ellis-on-castlevania-the-legacy-of-hammer-h.html |title=Warren Ellis on Castlevania, the Legacy of Hammer Horror, and the Creative Liberation of Writing for Netflix |first=Toussaint |last=Egan |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=Paste Magazine}}</ref> Ellis explained how he worked with ''Castlevania'' producer [[Koji Igarashi]] to fit the film into the timeline of the series, including writing a new backstory, and how he was frustrated that Igarashi wanted eight full re-writes of pre-production material before giving approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/7/7/15934226/netflix-castlevania|title=Netflix's new Castlevania series is the most bingeable show at just under 100 minutes|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2017-07-07|website=Polygon|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> Ellis noted that Frederator's Kevin Kolde, who was slated to produce the work, did not want the film to be aimed at children, allowing Ellis to use gruesome imagery and scenes as necessary to tell the story he wanted to write, something that Ellis had found restrictive in working with normal television animation.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nIn adapting the game for the film, Ellis did not want to make a point-for-point adaption, but instead provide some material to flesh out the game's world and elements behind it. At this stage, the film was anticipated to be only 80 minutes long, which Ellis knew would not be enough to tell the full story he wanted, so was able to break apart his script into a trilogy of works, each part having a self-contained [[three-act structure]]; the first part would be to introduce the characters of Dracula, Trevor, Sypha, and Alucard and with a meaningful narrative resolution. In this manner, Ellis noted that if the other two parts were never greenlit, the first work \"doesn't demand the presence of the other two parts for it to work as its own thing\".<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/02/09/first-time-warren-ellis-wrote-castlevania-animation-ten-years-ago/ |title=The First Time Warren Ellis Wrote A Castlevania Animation, Ten Years Ago |first=Rich |last=Johnson |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |website=[[Bleeding Cool News]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311002425/https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/02/09/first-time-warren-ellis-wrote-castlevania-animation-ten-years-ago/ |archivedate=March 11, 2017 }}</ref> Due to the limited time, Ellis opted to drop [[Grant DaNasty|Grant Danasty]], a pirate character in the game; Ellis noted that besides \"the stupid name\", he felt the pirate was misplaced in the setting and that the limited run time would not allow him to develop the character fully.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nSometime around 2008, work on the production stalled, and entered [[development hell]].<ref name=\"dtoid\">{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/10-years-of-purgatory-wasn-t-enough-to-keep-netflix-s-castlevania-down-447906.phtml | title = 10 years of purgatory wasn't enough to keep Netflix's Castlevania down | first = Peter | last = Glagowski | date = July 10, 2017 | accessdate = July 10, 2017 | website = [[Destructoid]] }}</ref> Ellis had completed his script in June 2008, and the show's production blog had said in August 2008 that they were shopping around the idea as a theatrical release, but no further updates followed before the blog was quietly deleted.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nAround 2012, [[Adi Shankar]] was approached to direct a live-action version of Ellis' script. Shankar, who at the time had just finished work as executive producer of ''[[Dredd]]'', said that the party was looking to make a film in the style of the ''[[Underworld (film series)|Underworld]]'' films with a similar budget, representative of a small studio with large independent backing. Shankar turned the opportunity down, saying it felt \"250 percent wrong\", as he had deep respect for the original game and felt the live-action version would not treat it well.<ref name=\"polygon july11\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/7/11/15952898/castlevania-live-action-adaptation-netflix | title = Castlevania producer turned down live-action adaptation because 'it felt wrong' | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = July 11, 2017 | accessdate = July 11, 2017 | website = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> Following this, Shankar stepped back from Hollywood to pursue more self-published works, stating that \"the major studios were blatantly disrespecting fandom\" as a reason he turned down the offer.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/>\n\nThe show was revitalized when [[Powerhouse Animation Studios]]'s Sam Deats was able to negotiate a deal with [[Netflix]] for the production, using the existing scripts that had been written nearly a decade prior. Powerhouse reached out to Frederator to help with the show's production.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> According to Ellis, Netflix was very positive about his original scripts that he wrote in 2007, and so he had to only make a few changes to fit the Netflix format while staying true to the version of the script Konami had accepted.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> Shankar was approached with the opportunity to produce the work, which he took as neither Powerhouse or Frederator sought to restrict his creative vision from Ellis' scripts.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/><ref name=\"usgamer show\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-headed-to-netflix-in-2017-from-warren-ellis-and-adi-shankar |title=Castlevania Headed To Netflix in 2017, From Warren Ellis and Adi Shankar |first=Mike |last=Williams |date=February 8, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[US Gamer]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080538/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-headed-to-netflix-in-2017-from-warren-ellis-and-adi-shankar |archivedate=February 11, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore |first=Dave |title=Super Violent 'Castlevania' Animated Series Coming from Producer Adi Shankar |url=http://collider.com/castlevania-animated-series-adi-shankar/ |website=Collider.com |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826133759/http://collider.com/castlevania-animated-series-adi-shankar/ |archivedate=August 26, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Melrose |first=Kevin |title=Castlevania TV Series Seemingly Confirmed By Adventure Time Producer |url=http://www.cbr.com/castlevania-tv-series-seemingly-confirmed-by-adventure-time-producer |website=CBR.com |accessdate=December 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161453/http://www.cbr.com/castlevania-tv-series-seemingly-confirmed-by-adventure-time-producer/ |archivedate=December 31, 2016 }}</ref> [[Fred Seibert]] and Kevin Kolde of Frederator Studios also co-produce.<ref name=\"usgamer show\"/> The series was animated by Frederator Studios and Powerhouse Animation Studios and directed by Sam Deats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://channelfrederator.frederator.com/post/161057646101/frederator-studios-in-darkness-a-hero-returns|title=Channel Frederator|website=Channel Frederator|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Castlevania (TV Series 2017\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6517102/companycredits|accessdate=2017-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/animating-guru-hirsh-is-back-with-new-company-netflix-project/article33942446/ |title=Animating guru Hirsh is back with new company, Netflix project |first=Martin |last=Knelman |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207230437/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/animating-guru-hirsh-is-back-with-new-company-netflix-project/article33942446/ |archivedate=February 7, 2017 }}</ref> [[Trevor Morris (musician)|Trevor Morris]] composed the show's music.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/>\n\nThe show's art style was heavily influenced by the work [[Ayami Kojima]] did for ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]''.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> They also took ideas from director [[Satoshi Kon]]'s works for character expressions and series such as ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]'' and ''[[Berserk: The Golden Age Arc|Berserk]]'' for inserting humor among the more serious elements.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> The show is produced using 2D [[hand-drawn animation]], taking cues from ''[[Ninja Scroll]]'' and ''[[Vampire Hunter D#Adaptations|Vampire Hunter D]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2017/07/19/interview-adi-shankar-discusses-castlevania-and-assassin-s-creed/|title=Interview: Adi Shankar Discusses Castlevania And Assassin's Creed|website=WWG}}</ref> with staff members that previously worked on ''[[Vampire Hunter D: Bloodlust]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2017/05/25/new-netflix-castlevania-animated-series-goes-full-on-vampire-hunter-d-and-looks-suitably-great/|title=New Netflix 'Castlevania' Animated Series Goes Full On 'Vampire Hunter D' And Looks Suitably Great|first=Ollie|last=Barder|publisher=}}</ref> The [[manga]] series ''[[Berserk (manga)|Berserk]]'' and ''[[Blade of the Immortal]]'' were also cited as inspiration, with one of the show's animation directors having previously worked on the [[Berserk: The Golden Age Arc|''Berserk'' films]].<ref name=\"io9\">{{cite news |last=Narcisse |first=Evan |title=The Animation Studio That Made Castlevania Explains Why It Was a Dream Project |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-animation-studio-that-made-castlevania-explains-why-1797476526 |work=[[io9]] |agency=[[Gizmodo]] |date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> The production works closely with [[Konami]], the holders of the ''Castlevania'' franchise, who helped to identify small continuity issues but were otherwise very receptive towards the work.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/>\n\nThe first season of four 30-minute episodes was released on July 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jacob|title=Netflix Quietly Announces Castlevania Series For 2017|url=http://www.cbr.com/netflix-quietly-announces-castlevania-series-for-2017|website=CBR.com|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> This season represents the first part of the trilogy that Ellis has laid out in 2007.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> The second season is eight episodes long and was released on October 26, 2018.<ref name=\"deadlines2\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/castlevania-animated-series-renewed-season-2-netflix-1202125024/| title='Castlevania' Animated Series Renewed For Season 2 By Netflix| first=Denise| last=Petski| date=July 7, 2017| website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/netflix-announces-castlevania-animated-series |title=Netflix Announces Animated Castlevania Series |first=Jonathan |last=Dornbrush |date=February 8, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209003832/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/netflix-announces-castlevania-animated-series |archivedate=February 9, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-the-first-trailer-for-netflixs-castlevania-s/1100-6450314/ |title=Watch The First Trailer For Netflix's Castlevania Show; Release Date Announced |first=Chris |last=Pereira |date=May 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626174614/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-the-first-trailer-for-netflixs-castlevania-s/1100-6450314/ |archivedate=June 26, 2017 }}</ref> Ellis said that the second season, completing the trilogy, is where he had been able to deviate somewhat from the game, and has been better anticipate the show's release on Netflix in terms of scenes and episode lengths.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> Shankar believes that there is an opportunity for more stories to be told borrowing from other games in the series, noting that overall he sees the series as \"a story about a family and multiple generations of this family\" with many tales to draw from.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/> The production team for the second season included staff members who worked on [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]] productions such as ''[[Death Parade]]''.<ref name=\"io9\"/>\n\nDeveloping the character of Dracula, [[Adi Shankar]] made it clear that one of the series' main goals has been to paint Dracula not as a villain, but a tragic, doomed figure. According to him: \"The best villains, in general, are the heroes of their own story and the trick to making ''Castlevania'' resonate was this idea that Dracula isn't a bad guy, he isn't a villain, he's just a person consumed with darkness. That first episode in Season 1 we start to see why he wants to eradicate humans. He's not just this mustache-curling, one-dimensional villain. What Dracula is doing is not really a war against humanity. It's more a suicide note.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/10/27/castlevania-season-2-showrunner-on-why-dracula-is-consumed-with-darkness | title = Castlevania Season 2: Showrunner on Why Dracula Is 'Consumed With Darkness' | first = Jesse | last = Schedeen | date = October 27, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\nThe show's third season was greenlit by Netflix a few days after the broadcast of the second season.<ref name=\"s3 greenlit\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/10/castlevania-renewed-season-3-netflix-richard-armitage-james-callis-1202493302/ | title = \u2018Castlevania\u2019 Renewed For Season 3 On Netflix | first=  Erik | last = Pederson | date = October 31, 2018 | accessdate = October 31, 2018 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] }}</ref> Shankar announced in November 2018 that he will also be leading an animated series based on Capcom's ''[[Devil May Cry]]'', which he acquired the rights for himself, and will make the show, alongside the ''Castlevania'' series, part of a shared \"[[Bootleg Multiverse]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/16/devil-may-cry-series-joins-castlevania-in-new-multiverse-from-adi-shankar | title = Devil May Cry Series Joins Castlevania In New Multiverse From Adi Shankar | first = David | last = Griffin | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> The third season was released on March 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elfring |first=Matt |title=Here's What's New to Netflix in March 2020: Castlevania Season 3, More Movies, TV Shows, and Originals |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/heres-whats-new-to-netflix-in-march-2020-castlevan/1100-6473892/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=6 March 2020 |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Audience viewership===\nAccording to Parrot Analytics, ''Castlevania'' was the most popular digital original series in the [[United States]] during July 6{{ndash}}19, 2017, with the show generating 23,175,616 \"demand expressions\" on average.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime-style Netflix series 'Castlevania' proved to be a hit with audiences|url=http://foundremote.com/anime-style-netflixs-series-castlevania-proved-to-be-a-hit-with-audiences/|website=Found Remote|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> According to Parrot Analytics, \"demand expressions\" indicate the \"total audience demand being expressed for a title, within a country,\"<ref name=\"parrotanalytics\">{{cite web|title=The Global Television Demand Report|url=https://insights.parrotanalytics.com/hubfs/Resources/whitepapers/Parrot%20Analytics%20-%20The%20Global%20TV%20Demand%20Report%202017.pdf|website=Parrot Analytics|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> measured by video streams and downloads as well as social media.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Netflix's 'Ozark' Was Most Popular Streaming Show This Summer, According to New Audience Metric|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/netflix-ratings-nielsen-defenders-full-house-house-of-cards-1201888675/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt remained the 7th most in-demand digital original show in the United States through October 11, 2017.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> By the end of 2017, ''Castlevania'' was the year's 15th most in-demand digital original series in the United States, averaging 18,137,196 demand expressions throughout the year. It was also one of the year's top{{nbsp}}20 most in-demand digital original series in the [[United Kingdom]] (20th), [[Japan]] (4th), [[Brazil]] (10th), [[Mexico]] (11th), [[France]] (13th), [[Canada]] (14th), [[Germany]] (19th) and [[Australia]] (20th).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Global Television Demand Report|url=https://insights.parrotanalytics.com/hubfs/Resources/whitepapers/Parrot%20Analytics%20-%20The%20Global%20TV%20Demand%20Report%202017.pdf|website=Parrot Analytics|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the second season became available in 2018, ''Castlevania'' had reportedly garnered nearly 30{{nbsp}}million viewers worldwide according to Netflix analytics, becoming one of the most successful original animated shows on Netflix.<ref>{{cite news |title=30 Years Later: From Nintendo to Netflix, \u2018Castlevania III: Dracula\u2019s Curse\u2019 Unfolds a New Legacy |url=https://goombastomp.com/30-years-later-from-nintendo-to-netflix-castlevania-iii-draculas-curse-unfolds-a-new-legacy/comment-page-1/ |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=Goomba Stomp |date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 80% of critics have given the first season a positive review based on 25 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 7.39/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"''Castlevania'' offers spectacular visuals and a compelling adaptation in its all-too-short first season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/castlevania/s01 |title=Castlevania: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref> It is the first video game adaptation in the site's history to receive a \"Fresh\" rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/netflix-castlevania-broke-rotten-tomatoes-record/ |title= Netflix animated series just lifted a curse: It's the first video game adaptation to get a Fresh rating |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which assigns a rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, reported that there were \"generally favorable reviews\" for the first season, with an weighted average score of 71 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/castlevania |title=Castlevania - TV Show Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Verge]]'' gave a mixed review, noting that the gore did little to create a sense of danger and felt \"intentionally flashy\". It concluded that \"''Castlevania'' is ripe with potential, but also burdened with cliches.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15938192/netflix-castlevania-review-animated-video-game-adaptation |title=Netflix's Castlevania isn't a perfect video game adaptation, but it's on the right track |first=Michael |last=Moore |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062348/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15938192/netflix-castlevania-review-animated-video-game-adaptation |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> Dave Trumbore of [[Collider (website)|Collider]] gave the series four stars out of five, praising the chemistry between the cast and comparing the violence with anime such as ''[[Ninja Scroll]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/castlevania-review-netflix/ |title='Castlevania' Review: Netflix's Video Game Adaptation Has Some Serious Bite |first=Dave |last=Trumbore |date=July 8, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=Collider |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708165546/http://collider.com/castlevania-review-netflix/ |archivedate=July 8, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' also wrote glowingly of Warren Ellis's script, but felt some of his humor was a little jarring.<ref name=\"IGNReview\"/> In a review for ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]'', Dave Raposo wrote that ''Castlevania'' channeled the cutaway gag formula that is seen in ''[[Family Guy]]''. He dismissed the \"absurd\" attempts at humanizing Dracula and called it a \"milquetoast imitation of ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\", noting that the ambitions of the script \"fly in the face of the simple ideals that unify the best entries in the ''Castlevania'' series\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/08/netflixs-castlevania-series-forgets-what-makes-the.html |title=Netflix's Castlevania Series Forgets What Makes the Games Work |first=Dave |last=Raposo |date=September 7, 2017 |accessdate=September 7, 2017 |website=Paste Magazine}}</ref> Several reviews lauded the voice cast, particularly Graham McTavish as Dracula and Richard Armitage as Trevor Belmont.<ref name=\"IGNReview\">{{cite web |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/07/09/castlevania-season-1-review |title=CASTLEVANIA: SEASON 1 REVIEW |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen |date=July 8, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref> ''[[Screen Rant]]''{{'s}} Sarah Moran drew attention to the \"sarcastic edge\" that Armitage brought to the character, and also noted Callis's \"air of sophistication\" as Alucard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/castlevania-netflix-season-1-review/ |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 1: Every Episode Reviewed |first=Sarah |last=Moran |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=Screen Rant |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062409/http://screenrant.com/castlevania-netflix-season-1-review/ |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[Destructoid]]'' also wrote positively of Trevor Belmont as a protagonist, but criticized the animation and added that the character designs were \"flat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-castlevania-season-1--445745.phtml |title=Review: Castlevania (Season 1) |first=Nick |last=Valdez |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=[[Destructoid]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709050453/https://www.destructoid.com/review-castlevania-season-1--445745.phtml |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> Dan Seitz at [[Uproxx]] left a negative review, writing that it tried too hard to find profundity in the story of the ''Castlevania'' series. He also cited issues with the pacing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/castlevania-netflix/ |title=Netflix's 'Castlevania' Tries Too Hard To Make A Silly Game Profound |first=Dan |last=Seitz |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |website=Uproxx |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062404/http://uproxx.com/hitfix/castlevania-netflix/ |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRotten Tomatoes reported that 100% of critics have given the second season a positive review with an average rating of 9.73/10, based on 12 reviews. The critics consensus reads, \"''Castlevania'' sinks its fangs into vampiric lore during a devilishly fun second season that benefits from an expanded sense of scale and episode tally that allows the series to fully spread its leathery wings.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/castlevania/s02 |title=Castlevania: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nComplaints were made towards the pacing and the screen time spent on Dracula's court in season two. Writing for ''[[GameSpot]]'', Michael Rougeau was disappointed that Trevor's group spent the majority of their time in a library, and also said Dracula \"does literally nothing in all the episodes we've seen so far. There's one medium length flashback in which he massacres a council of merchants who offended him, but it's not like that moves the story along\". Rougeau concluded that the action was creatively executed, but he felt that the new cast was given more development and that the previous characters were left to \"tread water\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/netflixs-castlevania-season-2-full-review-dark-met/1100-6462640 |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 2 Full Review: Dark Metamorphosis |first=Michael |last=Rougeau |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=GameSpot}}</ref> [[Film School Rejects]] echoed similar sentiments, who said the second season was more of a complement to the first one. McTavish and the rest of the voice cast were once again met with high praise.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/castlevania-season-2-review/ |title='Castlevania' Season 2 Review: Blood, Guts, and Backstory |first=Meg |last=Shields |date=October 20, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=Film School Rejects}}</ref> In Collider's review for the second series, Dave Trumbore mentioned there \"isn't a weak link in the cast here\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/castlevania-season-2-review/ |title='Castlevania' Season 2 Review: Bigger, Bloodier, and with More Bite Than Ever |first=Dave |last=Trumbore |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=Collider}}</ref> ''[[WhatCulture]]'' wrote very positively of the voice work and also noted the new performances, including Jaime Murray as Carmilla and Adetokumboh M'Cormack as Isaac.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/tv/castlevania-season-2-review-7-ups-and-2-downs?page=4 |title=Castlevania Season 2 Review: 7 Ups And 2 Downs |first=Motzie |last=Dapul |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=WhatCulture}}</ref> ''IGN'' gave the second season a 9.2/10, praising Ellis's approach to ''Castlevania'' as \"witty and self-aware enough to poke fun at itself when necessary\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2018/10/26/netflixs-castlevania-season-2-review |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 2 Review |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=IGN}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bootleg Multiverse]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/80095241''Castlevania''] on [[Netflix]]\n* {{IMDB title|tt6517102}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Castlevania series}}\n{{Frederator Studios}}\n{{Powerhouse Animation Studios}}\n{{Adaptations of Dracula}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American adult animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated horror television series]]\n[[Category:Animated series based on video games]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animated television series]]\n[[Category:Castlevania]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:Dracula television programmes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Warren Ellis]]\n[[Category:Frederator Studios]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in fiction]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 15th century]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Europe]]\n[[Category:Vampires in animated television]]\n[[Category:Viz Media anime]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in television]]\n[[Category:Works based on Konami video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American adult animated series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Castlevania\n| image                    = Castlevania netflix titlecard.png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]<br />[[Dark fantasy]]<br />[[Action film|Action]]<br />[[Adventure film|Adventure]]<br />[[Horror fiction|Horror]]\n| developer                = [[Adi Shankar]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Castlevania]]''|[[Konami]]}}\n| writer                   = [[Warren Ellis]]\n| director                 = {{plainlist|\n* Sam Deats\n* Adam Deats\n* Spencer Wan\n}}\n| voices                   = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list --> {{plainlist|\n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]]\n* [[James Callis]]\n* [[Graham McTavish]]\n* Alejandra Reynoso\n* [[Tony Amendola]]\n* [[Matt Frewer]]\n* [[Emily Swallow]]\n* [[Theo James]]\n* [[Adetokumboh M'Cormack]]\n* [[Jaime Murray]]\n* [[Peter Stormare]]\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Trevor Morris (musician)|Trevor Morris]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 3<!-- Increment when new seasons/series begin. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| num_episodes             = 22<!-- Value is incremented when new episodes air. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{unbulleted list|[[Adi Shankar]]|[[Fred Seibert]]|Ted Biaselli|Kevin Kolde|[[Larry Tanz]]|Warren Ellis}}\n| producer                 = Toshiyuki Hiruma<br/>Maki Terashima<br/>Brad Graeber<br />Jason Williams\n| runtime                  = 23\u201331 minutes\n| company                  = {{unbulleted list|[[Frederator Studios]]|[[Powerhouse Animation Studios]]|Shankar Animation|Project 51 Productions|Mua Film}}\n| distributor              = [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n| network                  = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| related                  = [[Bootleg Multiverse]]\n| website                  = <!-- Remove or comment out this parameter line completely if URL exists on or is moved to Wikidata -->\n| production_website       = \n}}\n'''''Castlevania''''' is an American [[Adult animation|adult animated]] [[web television|web]] [[television series]] based on the Japanese video game series [[Castlevania|of the same name]] by [[Konami]]. The first two seasons adapt the 1989 entry ''[[Castlevania III: Dracula's Curse]]'' and follow [[Trevor Belmont]], [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Alucard]] and [[Sypha Belnades]] as they defend the nation of [[Wallachia]] from [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Dracula]] and his minions. Seasons 2 and 3 borrow characters and elements from the 2005 entry ''[[Castlevania: Curse of Darkness]]''.\n\nThe series was originally planned as a film, developed by producer Kevin Kolde and his company Project 51. Kolde had a contract for a script with writer [[Warren Ellis]] in 2007; the project entered [[development hell]] until about 2015, when [[Adi Shankar]] boarded the project and it was picked up by streaming service [[Netflix]]. [[Powerhouse Animation Studios]] joined the team and production commenced. Its art style is heavily influenced by Japanese [[anime]] and [[Ayami Kojima]]'s artwork in ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]'' with the production team including staff members who worked in the Japanese anime industry.\n\nThe series premiered on Netflix on July 7, 2017, and was renewed for an expanded second season of eight episodes on the same day; the second season premiered on October 26, 2018. A ten-episode third season was greenlit by Netflix and released on March 5, 2020. On March 27, 2020, Netflix announced they have renewed the series for a fourth season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2020/03/27/castlevania-season-4-netflix/|title=Netflix Announces Castlevania Season 4|website=Anime|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nWhen his wife is burned at the stake after being falsely accused of witchcraft, the vampire Count [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Dracula]] declares all the people of [[Wallachia]] will pay with their lives. He summons an army of demons which overruns the country, causing the people to live lives of fear and distrust. To combat this, the outcast monster hunter [[Trevor Belmont]] takes up arms against Dracula's forces, aided by the [[magician (fantasy)|magician]] [[Sypha Belnades]] and Dracula's [[dhampir]] son [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Alucard]].\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{further|List of Castlevania characters}}\n* [[Richard Armitage (actor)|Richard Armitage]] as [[Trevor Belmont]], the last living member of the Belmont clan, an excommunicated family of monster hunters.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/castlevania-animated-netflix-cast-graham-mctavish/|title=Netflix 'Castlevania' Voice Cast Includes 'Preacher,' 'Hannibal' Alum|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Kevin|date=June 28, 2017|website=Screen Crush|accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[James Callis]] as [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Adrian Alucard Tepes]], the [[dhampir]] son of Dracula and Lisa Tepes, who seeks to protect humanity from his father.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Graham McTavish]] as [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Vlad Dracula Tepes]], a vampire who swears vengeance on humanity for the death of his wife Lisa, summoning an army of monsters to destroy all the people of Wallachia. (season 1 - 2)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* Alejandra Reynoso as [[Sypha Belnades]], a Speaker and the Elder's granddaughter who wields powerful magic.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Tony Amendola]] as The Elder, the leader of a group of Speakers aiding the people of Gresit whom Trevor befriends.<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" /> (season 1)\n* [[Matt Frewer]] as The Bishop, a psychotic clergyman who orders the burning of Lisa Tepes for witchcraft, later being named the bishop of Gresit. (season 1)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Emily Swallow]] as [[Lisa (Castlevania)|Lisa Tepes]], Dracula's beloved wife who is burned at the stake after being falsely accused of witchcraft. (season 1)<ref name=\"Voice Cast\" />\n* [[Theo James]] as [[Hector (Castlevania)|Hector]], a devil forgemaster called upon to serve Dracula in his war against humanity. He has a hatred of humanity, but his na\u00efvet\u00e9 makes him easy to deceive or manipulate.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/castlevania-season-2-voice-cast-characters/|title=Castlevania Season 2 Voice Cast and Character Guide|last=Donaldson|first=Kayleigh|date=October 26, 2018|website=Screen Rant|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Adetokumboh M'Cormack]] as [[Isaac (Castlevania)|Isaac]], a rivalrous devil forgemaster and fierce loyalist of Dracula who helps to lead his army.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Jaime Murray]] as [[Carmilla (Castlevania)|Carmilla]], a scheming vampire mistress and member of Dracula's war council who seeks to usurp him.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2 \u2013 present)\n* [[Peter Stormare]] as Godbrand, a viking vampire warlord called upon to serve Dracula in the battle against Wallachia.<ref name=\"Voice Cast Season 2\" /> (season 2)\n* [[Jessica Brown Findlay]] as Lenore, the diplomat member of the Council of Sisters. She is in charge of subduing Hector. (season 3)\n* [[Yasmine Al Massri]] as Morana, the strategist member of the Council of Sisters. (season 3)\n* [[Ivana Milicevic]] as Striga, the military member of the Council of Sisters. (season 3)\n* [[Bill Nighy]] as [[List of Castlevania characters#Saint Germain|Saint Germain]], a strange man investigating the priory of Lindenfeld. (season 3)\n* [[Navid Negahban]] as Sala, the leader of the monks of Lindenfeld who actually seeks to resurrect Dracula. (season 3)\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as The Judge, the town leader of Lindenfeld who wishes to keep peace and order in town. (season 3)\n* Toru Uchikado as Taka, a vampire hunter from Japan using a bow. (season 3)\n* [[Rila Fukushima]] as Sumi, a vampire hunter from Japan using a sword. (season 3)\n* [[Barbara Steele]] as Miranda, an old woman possessing magic powers who helps Isaac. (season 3)\n* [[Lance Reddick]] as The Captain, a pirate captain who befriends and helps Isaac. (season 3)\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| released    = y\n| allreleased = y\n\n| color1      = #420701\n| link1       = #Season 1 (2017)\n| episodes1   = 4\n| start1      = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n\n| color2      = #770101\n| link2       = #Season 2 (2018)\n| episodes2   = 8\n| start2      = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n\n| color3      = #5F5149\n| link3       = #Season 3 (2020)\n| episodes3   = 10\n| start3      = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2017)===\n{{Episode table |background=#420701 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Witchbottle\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = In [[Wallachia]] in 1455, a young woman named [[List of Castlevania characters#Lisa|Lisa]] who wishes to be a doctor seeks out [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Vlad Dracula Tepes]], a vampire with advanced scientific knowledge. Intrigued by her courage and ambition, Dracula agrees to teach her, while she in turn offers to help him reconnect with humanity. The two eventually fall in love and marry. Twenty years later (1475), in the town of [[T\u00e2rgovi\u0219te]], Lisa is burned at the stake after a bishop discovers scientific equipment in her home and accuses her of witchcraft. Dracula is devastated and furious upon learning of his wife's death and declares the people have one year to make their peace, after which every human in Wallachia will die by his hand. His son [[Alucard (Castlevania)|Adrian]] tells him to instead go after the man responsible instead of all of humanity, but Dracula refuses to listen and attacks him. One year later, the archbishop hosts a celebration in defiance of Dracula. As promised, Dracula kills the archbishop, destroys the church and orders his demon army to kill every person left in Wallachia. As the army spreads across the land, the people place the blame on the kingdom's noble families, including the Belmonts.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Necropolis\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Following an altercation at a pub, [[Trevor Belmont]] seeks food and respite in the city of Gresit, which has been besieged by Dracula's forces every night. As he passes through town, he learns that the townspeople blame a group of magic users known as the Speakers for Dracula's assault. He saves their Elder from a pair of corrupt priests, who brings him back to his home to meet his fellow Speakers. Trevor insists they leave the city for their own safety, but the Elder refuses, as his grandchild has gone missing after venturing into the catacombs below the city in search of the \"sleeping soldier\", a legendary hero who they believe can defeat Dracula. Begrudgingly, Trevor agrees to retrieve the missing grandchild.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Labyrinth\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Exploring the catacombs, Trevor realizes that they have been unusually constructed and contain devices matching old family descriptions of devices within Dracula's castle. Finding a stone statue in the visage of a Speaker, Trevor is attacked by a giant cyclops. He defeats the creature, releasing its curse, and rescues the Elder's grandchild, [[Sypha Belnades]]. After returning Sypha to her grandfather, Trevor is summoned to the church by the local bishop, the same bishop who ordered Lisa's execution. He orders Trevor to leave Gresit before sundown, as they plan to lead a mob to kill the Speakers, offering to spare Trevor and restore his family name in exchange. With the Speakers refusing to retreat, Trevor has them hidden in the cyclops' chamber and takes on the priests leading the mob before escaping into the city.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Monument\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|7|7}}\n |ShortSummary    = Night falls as Dracula's army descends upon Gresit, killing the bishop. As Trevor continues his escape, Sypha appears to aid him, revealing herself as a powerful magic user. Trevor exposes the clergy's actions as the true reason for Dracula's invasion and assists the people in mounting a defense against the demons. During the battle, the floor crumbles beneath Trevor and Sypha and they fall deep into the submerged catacombs of the city. Making their way in deeper, they find the \"sleeping soldier\", revealed to be Adrian, who has spent a year healing from his last fight with Dracula. Adrian, now going by Alucard, engages Trevor in battle, but after seeing his and Sypha's resolve, Alucard relents and reveals that he was testing their abilities because the myth of the \"sleeping soldier\" was actually from the future and foretold Alucard's meeting with Belmont and Sypha. The three prepare to challenge Dracula and end the conflict for good.\n |LineColor       = 420701\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2 (2018)===\n{{Episode table |background=#770101 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = War Council\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = A flashback depicts Lisa's home in [[Cerg\u0103u|Lupu]] being raided by the Bishop and his men while Dracula is away, resulting in her arrest to be tried before an inquisition. In the present, Dracula assembles his war council, made up of vampire overlords from across the world, and places human necromancers Hector and Isaac in charge of the war on humanity. The viking vampire Godbrand objects, believing they should rely on vampires instead of humans for leadership, but Dracula believes Hector and Isaac's hatred of their own kind makes them more trustworthy. As Gresit rebuilds after the battle, Sypha and Trevor see off the other Speakers while Alucard comes to terms with the decision to kill his father. At the castle, Godbrand laments to Hector that their war is being fought with no strategy apart from wanton destruction. Hector implies that Dracula wants all humans dead no matter the methods used, to Godbrand's disappointment. Dracula teleports the castle to a different location.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = Old Homes\n |DirectedBy      = Spencer Wan\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor and Sypha reunite with Alucard and ask how to locate Dracula's castle when it can move from place to place. Trevor recommends revisiting his old family estate, as the hold beneath the ruins contains plenty of information and tools for monster-hunting. At Dracula's castle, the vampire mistress Carmilla arrives and causes further discord among the council by criticizing Dracula's approach and inquiring his reasons of having not sired Lisa into a vampire. While traveling to the Belmont estate, Trevor's party is attacked by Dracula's forces; the group slays all the attackers, save one injured demon who escapes. At the castle, Isaac reminisces on his past, having killed his previous abusive master in a moment that shaped his ideals. Godbrand brings Isaac the injured demon, now dead, to extract information from it with his necromancy. At another assembly, the generals argue whether to continue their attack on [[Arge\u0219 County|Arge\u0219]] or move the siege towards [[Br\u0103ila County|Br\u0103ila]] at Carmilla's suggestion. Isaac informs everyone of his findings, believing Alucard is working with a Belmont. Carmilla urges Dracula to keep watch on the Belmont estate, believing it may contain something that could destroy them.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Shadow Battles\n |DirectedBy      = Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Carmilla tries to convince Hector to create creatures to send to the Belmont house while encouraging Dracula to select Br\u0103ila as their next target. Hector reminisces on how Dracula found him in the east of [[Rhodes]] and recruited him to raise an army, though Hector asked for a humane cull of humans rather than a cruel genocide. Trevor, Sypha and Alucard reach the ruins of the Belmont estate and open a magically-sealed door leading to a massive underground library. Sypha begins researching and Trevor locates several monster-hunting weapons, including the Morning Star whip, while Alucard is left uneasy by the various vampire remains preserved there. At Dracula's castle, Godbrand expresses his dissatisfaction with the plan to exterminate the human race, believing they will be left hungry without human blood to consume, and Dracula rebukes him. Carmilla tells Godbrand that Dracula must take the castle to Br\u0103ila, revealing how she killed the vampire who sired her after he became old and mad, deeming Dracula has become the same and unfit to lead them.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = Broken Mast\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Godbrand comes to agree with Carmilla that Dracula is not fit to lead and something must be done to change his plans. At the Belmont library, Trevor discovers a magical mirror which allows them to see things far away, and he bonds with Sypha. Carmilla continues to try to recruit Hector, intending to unseat Dracula if the castle is moved to Br\u0103ila. In a flashback, Isaac recalls how Dracula saved his life and recruited him to create his army. Godbrand and the other vampire generals grow tired of living without human blood and set out on demonic horses to a nearby village, slaughtering the people. Dracula speaks to Isaac about the war hall turning against him and confesses he lied to Hector about his intent to spare a few humans. Godbrand privately approaches Isaac and suggests that they should pursue the war without Dracula, Isaac killing Godbrand for his treasonous intentions.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = Last Spell\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Isaac releases Godbrand's ashes from the castle rooftop while Carmilla commands her troops to assemble at Br\u0103ila. Hector convinces Isaac to agree to the attack on Br\u0103ila. Hector feeds this back to Carmilla and informs her that his night creatures have nearly reached the Belmont estate. Isaac discusses Hector's request with Dracula, but asserts that there is no betrayal to be concerned about. Dracula reminisces about a time he once savored killing humans but admits he is tired and cares only for results instead of the details. Carmilla and Hector approach Dracula and he approves the attack on Br\u0103ila. Afterwards, Carmilla turns on Hector, explaining he is now implicated in her impending betrayal of Dracula and cannot turn back on her plan now. At the Belmont library, Sypha discovers an unfinished locking spell that could be used to trap the castle in one place. The library starts to shake as Hector's night creatures arrive and attempt to break in.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = The River\n |DirectedBy      = Spencer Wan\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor fights off the demons as Alucard uses the distance mirror to locate Dracula's castle so Sypha can attempt to complete the locking spell. Dracula moves the castle to Br\u0103ila, and most of the vampire generals lead troops across the bridge to attack the town. At Carmilla's behest, Hector reanimates the Bishop and makes him bless the river. Carmilla's troops reveal themselves and bring down the bridge, dropping many of Dracula's soldiers to be destroyed by the now-holy water. Dracula's remaining forces retreat to the castle whilst Carmilla's soldiers cross the river on makeshift bridges. The two armies begin to battle in the castle's main hall, while Carmilla and Hector move elsewhere. Sypha finishes the spell just as Trevor defeats the last of the demons, her struggle against the castle's mechanisms causing the castle to teleport within Br\u0103ila, landing in the river with most of the vampires of both factions killed by the holy water flooding into the castle. Sypha succeeds, disabling the castle's mechanisms while relocating it above the Belmont library.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n |Title           = For Love\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Emerging from the library, Trevor, Sypha and Alucard storm the castle and defeat the remaining vampires in the main hall. Dracula retreats to his study with Isaac, whom he sends through his magic mirror back to the desert to save the human from sacrificing himself to defend Dracula from death. Alucard reaches the study and attacks Dracula, backed by Trevor and Sypha. The group manages to inflict some damage, but Dracula overpowers them, and engages in hand-to-hand combat with Alucard, moving through the castle as they battle. Eventually the two end up in Alucard's childhood room where Dracula has a break down upon realizing the reality of him trying to kill his own son. Dracula allows Alucard to stake him through the heart, while Trevor arrives to decapitate the decomposing vampire and Sypha burns the remains, leaving only his wedding ring intact. Alucard is upset about having killed his father, but Trevor and Sypha reassure him it was the right thing to do as they all walk out of the castle as morning dawns.\n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n |Title           = End Times\n |DirectedBy      = Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alucard intends to make Dracula's now-deserted castle his grave, but Trevor gifts him the Belmont library along with encouragement to protect both their ancestral homes while using their collective knowledge to help people. Meanwhile, Isaac murders a group of raiders and turns them into the first of his personal army. In Br\u0103ila, Carmilla decides to return to [[Styria]], enslaving Hector for his skills to quickly rebuild her forces and take advantage of the power vacuum left by Dracula's demise. Sypha convinces Trevor to stay with her and join her on new adventures battling monsters, and they bid farewell to Alucard and set off to find the Speakers. Left alone in the castle, Alucard reflects on the loss of his family and is overcome by grief. \n |LineColor       = 770101\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 3 (2020)===\n{{Episode table |background=#5F5149 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=25 |director=24 |writer=15 |airdate=26 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = Bless Your Dead Little Hearts\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = [[Warren Ellis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = A month after Dracula\u2019s death, Alucard tries to adjust to his isolation, but he misses Trevor and Sypha. Meanwhile, Trevor and Sypha arrive in a small town of Lindenfield, where a local priory seems to sympathize Dracula\u2019s cause and wish to punish those responsible for his death. Carmilla returns to her castle in Styria with Hector to reunite with her Council of Sisters (consisting of herself, Lenore, Striga and Morana). Hector is then imprisoned in her castle.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = The Reparation of My Heart\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Somewhere in Northern Africa, Isaac is set on exacting revenge on Hector. He acquires a distance mirror, a magical device which reveals Hector's whereabouts. Isaac and his creatures then depart for Genoa on a boat belonging to a man known as the Captain. In Styria, Carmilla shares her plans to dominate an area of Eastern Europe, effectively enclosing it into a personal pen with humans as livestock. However, when Striga points out how Hector will refuse to forge new demons, Lenore volunteers to convince him otherwise. In Lindenfield, Trevor meets the mysterious Saint Germain, who recognizes him as a Belmont. Germain convinces the priory leader, Sala, to grant him access into the Priory. At the Belmont Hold, Alucard is visited by a pair of vampire hunters from Japan, Taka and Sumi.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n |Title           = Investigators\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Befriending the Judge of Lindenfield, Trevor and Sypha learn how an attack Dracula's creatures resulted in its leader, the Visitor, escaping to the priory, where it communicated with the monks. Since then, Sala began refusing townfolk into the priory\u2019s hall, instead allowing disturbed strangers into the monastery. On the open seas, the Captain and Isaac are debating the merits of humanity. When Isaac says he wishes to continue Dracula's ambitions, his faith is shaken when the Captain challenges him to use his skills to teach humanity how to be kinder. At Carmilla\u2019s castle, Lenore brings food to an unclothed and battered Hector. Wary of her intentions, he attempts to escape, only to be beaten down by Lenore.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n |Title           = I Have a Scheme\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = At Dracula\u2019s castle, Alucard learns from Taka and Sumi they were once enslaved by one of Dracula's council members, Ch\u014d. Although Ch\u014d died in the previous season, Taka and Sumi know another vampire will one day succeed her, and ask Alucard to teach them. Meanwhile, in Styria, relations between Hector and Lenore begin to thaw after she provides him with shoes. At the Lindenfield monastery, Saint Germain is wary of the monks, questioning their loyalty to God. He\u2019s fascinated by the symbol on Sala\u2019s armband (the alchemical sign for sulfur used by philosophers to denote Hell). Arriving at Genoa, Isaac is refused to leave in peace by the local men-at-arms, who he unleashes his creatures on.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 17\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n |Title           = A Seat of Civilisation and Refinement\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Trevor and Judge notice ominous symbols scattered throughout the town. Outside the monastery, Saint Germain meets Sypha, who knows he's a magician. He reveals to her that he recognizes the symbols as alchemical signs. Joined with Trevor, Saint Germain tells them that he\u2019s in search of a portal to \u201cthe Infinite Corridor\u201d, where he once lost someone dear to him, and that he\u2019s found one beneath the priory. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 18\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n |Title           = The Good Dream\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats & Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Lenore takes a now clothed Hector with a collar on his neck around Carmilla's castle, and he gradually starts to fall for her charms. In Lindenfield, Germain has a nightmare of falling through the Infinite Corridor an endless pit of dimensions where he witnesses worlds with giant monsters and spaceships. Before waking up, a woman from one of the worlds tosses a crystal to him.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 19\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n |Title           = Worse Things Than Betrayal\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alucard trains Sumi and Taka and takes them to the Belmont Hold, teaching them to start with something simple. Returning to the prior in Lindenfield, Saint Germain discovers an book with pages recently torn out which show to bring back the dead from Hell. He heads towards the basement, where he finds the Visitor impaled to the walls. During a two weeks march from Styra, Issac meets a blind woman, Miranda, who reveals a nearby city houses a magician who populates it with his own slaves. She tells him the Magician owns a transmission mirror, which can transport Isaac and his army to Styria.\n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 20\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n |Title           = What the Night Brings\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Saint Germain meets up with Trevor, Sypha and the Judge. They come up with a plan to fight the mad monks and also help Germain open the Infinite Corridor. In the Belmont hold, Alucard bonds with Taka and Sumi during their training, but they are both getting the feeling that Alucard is hiding something from them. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 21\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n |Title           = The Harvest\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats & Adam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = At sundown, the houses of Lindenfeld that bear the ominous carving combust into flames. A battle between the monks and the Judge's men begins, as countless monsters emerge from the Priory. Trevor, Sypha and Saint Germain enter the Priory, while the Visitor opens a portal to Hell where Dracula is seen holding his wife, Lisa. In Styria, Lenores tricks Hector by slipping a magic ring onto his finger as they having sex, which enslaves him. Isaac enter the city and his night creatures successfully defeat the Magician and his Legion, an amalgamation of countless human bodies. As Alucard lies awake at night in Dracula's castle, Taka and Sumi enter the room and proceed to have sex with him, but then soon seize the chance to restrain him with a trap. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 22\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n |Title           = Abandon All Hope\n |DirectedBy      = Sam Deats\n |WrittenBy       = Warren Ellis\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|5}}\n |ShortSummary    = Taka and Sumi accuse Alucard of witholding his knowledge of magic and not teaching them how to operate the castle. Before they can stake him, he uses his sword to kill them. Following their betrayal, Alucard is later seen prostate and weeping on the floor. In the Priory's basement, Trevor and Sypha battle the monsters while Saint Germain tries closing the portal. Sala stabs the Judge, who suddenly tells Sala about a secret path where he can make his escape. As Trevor kills the Visitor, Saint Germain closes the corridor with him inside, thanking Trevor and Sypha for their help. Later, Trevor and Sypha find Sala dead in a pit of spikes, with countless human bones. They discover the Judge had been killing children and taking their shoes as trophies to his house. After burning it down, they leave Lindenfeld. At Carmilla\u2019s castle, the sisters have perfected their plan, and Lenore presents them with rings she had forged to make Hector's night creatures loyal to them. The ring will also end Hector's life if he attempts escape. Having been manipulated, Hector is distraught at Lenore. The episode ends with Alucard at the castle's entrance, where he has left the bodies of Sumi and Taka impaled on spikes to ward off future visitors. \n |LineColor       = 5F5149\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Warren_Ellis_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg|thumb|175px|[[Warren Ellis]] wrote the series as a direct-to-video film before adapting it for a television format.]]\nIn March 2007, [[Frederator Studios]] acquired the rights to produce an animated film adaption of ''[[Castlevania III: Dracula's Curse]]'', intended as a [[direct-to-video]] production. Frederator brought writer [[Warren Ellis]] aboard as the screenwriter for the series. In an interview with ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'', Warren Ellis said that when he was contacted about ''Castlevania'' he had no previous knowledge of the series and discovered it was a \"Japanese transposition of the [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Horror films]] I grew up with and loved\".<ref name=\"paste magazine\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/07/warren-ellis-on-castlevania-the-legacy-of-hammer-h.html |title=Warren Ellis on Castlevania, the Legacy of Hammer Horror, and the Creative Liberation of Writing for Netflix |first=Toussaint |last=Egan |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=Paste Magazine}}</ref> Ellis explained how he worked with ''Castlevania'' producer [[Koji Igarashi]] to fit the film into the timeline of the series, including writing a new backstory, and how he was frustrated that Igarashi wanted eight full re-writes of pre-production material before giving approval.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/7/7/15934226/netflix-castlevania|title=Netflix's new Castlevania series is the most bingeable show at just under 100 minutes|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2017-07-07|website=Polygon|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> Ellis noted that Frederator's Kevin Kolde, who was slated to produce the work, did not want the film to be aimed at children, allowing Ellis to use gruesome imagery and scenes as necessary to tell the story he wanted to write, something that Ellis had found restrictive in working with normal television animation.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nIn adapting the game for the film, Ellis did not want to make a point-for-point adaption, but instead provide some material to flesh out the game's world and elements behind it. At this stage, the film was anticipated to be only 80 minutes long, which Ellis knew would not be enough to tell the full story he wanted, so was able to break apart his script into a trilogy of works, each part having a self-contained [[three-act structure]]; the first part would be to introduce the characters of Dracula, Trevor, Sypha, and Alucard and with a meaningful narrative resolution. In this manner, Ellis noted that if the other two parts were never greenlit, the first work \"doesn't demand the presence of the other two parts for it to work as its own thing\".<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/02/09/first-time-warren-ellis-wrote-castlevania-animation-ten-years-ago/ |title=The First Time Warren Ellis Wrote A Castlevania Animation, Ten Years Ago |first=Rich |last=Johnson |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |website=[[Bleeding Cool News]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311002425/https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/02/09/first-time-warren-ellis-wrote-castlevania-animation-ten-years-ago/ |archivedate=March 11, 2017 }}</ref> Due to the limited time, Ellis opted to drop [[Grant DaNasty|Grant Danasty]], a pirate character in the game; Ellis noted that besides \"the stupid name\", he felt the pirate was misplaced in the setting and that the limited run time would not allow him to develop the character fully.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nSometime around 2008, work on the production stalled, and entered [[development hell]].<ref name=\"dtoid\">{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/10-years-of-purgatory-wasn-t-enough-to-keep-netflix-s-castlevania-down-447906.phtml | title = 10 years of purgatory wasn't enough to keep Netflix's Castlevania down | first = Peter | last = Glagowski | date = July 10, 2017 | accessdate = July 10, 2017 | website = [[Destructoid]] }}</ref> Ellis had completed his script in June 2008, and the show's production blog had said in August 2008 that they were shopping around the idea as a theatrical release, but no further updates followed before the blog was quietly deleted.<ref name=\"bcn ellis 2007\"/>\n\nAround 2012, [[Adi Shankar]] was approached to direct a live-action version of Ellis' script. Shankar, who at the time had just finished work as executive producer of ''[[Dredd]]'', said that the party was looking to make a film in the style of the ''[[Underworld (film series)|Underworld]]'' films with a similar budget, representative of a small studio with large independent backing. Shankar turned the opportunity down, saying it felt \"250 percent wrong\", as he had deep respect for the original game and felt the live-action version would not treat it well.<ref name=\"polygon july11\">{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/7/11/15952898/castlevania-live-action-adaptation-netflix | title = Castlevania producer turned down live-action adaptation because 'it felt wrong' | first = Julia | last = Alexander | date = July 11, 2017 | accessdate = July 11, 2017 | website = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> Following this, Shankar stepped back from Hollywood to pursue more self-published works, stating that \"the major studios were blatantly disrespecting fandom\" as a reason he turned down the offer.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/>\n\nThe show was revitalized when [[Powerhouse Animation Studios]]'s Sam Deats was able to negotiate a deal with [[Netflix]] for the production, using the existing scripts that had been written nearly a decade prior. Powerhouse reached out to Frederator to help with the show's production.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> According to Ellis, Netflix was very positive about his original scripts that he wrote in 2007, and so he had to only make a few changes to fit the Netflix format while staying true to the version of the script Konami had accepted.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> Shankar was approached with the opportunity to produce the work, which he took as neither Powerhouse or Frederator sought to restrict his creative vision from Ellis' scripts.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/><ref name=\"usgamer show\">{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-headed-to-netflix-in-2017-from-warren-ellis-and-adi-shankar |title=Castlevania Headed To Netflix in 2017, From Warren Ellis and Adi Shankar |first=Mike |last=Williams |date=February 8, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[US Gamer]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080538/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/castlevania-headed-to-netflix-in-2017-from-warren-ellis-and-adi-shankar |archivedate=February 11, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore |first=Dave |title=Super Violent 'Castlevania' Animated Series Coming from Producer Adi Shankar |url=http://collider.com/castlevania-animated-series-adi-shankar/ |website=Collider.com |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826133759/http://collider.com/castlevania-animated-series-adi-shankar/ |archivedate=August 26, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Melrose |first=Kevin |title=Castlevania TV Series Seemingly Confirmed By Adventure Time Producer |url=http://www.cbr.com/castlevania-tv-series-seemingly-confirmed-by-adventure-time-producer |website=CBR.com |accessdate=December 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231161453/http://www.cbr.com/castlevania-tv-series-seemingly-confirmed-by-adventure-time-producer/ |archivedate=December 31, 2016 }}</ref> [[Fred Seibert]] and Kevin Kolde of Frederator Studios also co-produce.<ref name=\"usgamer show\"/> The series was animated by Frederator Studios and Powerhouse Animation Studios and directed by Sam Deats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://channelfrederator.frederator.com/post/161057646101/frederator-studios-in-darkness-a-hero-returns|title=Channel Frederator|website=Channel Frederator|language=en|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Castlevania (TV Series 2017\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6517102/companycredits|accessdate=2017-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/animating-guru-hirsh-is-back-with-new-company-netflix-project/article33942446/ |title=Animating guru Hirsh is back with new company, Netflix project |first=Martin |last=Knelman |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207230437/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/animating-guru-hirsh-is-back-with-new-company-netflix-project/article33942446/ |archivedate=February 7, 2017 }}</ref> [[Trevor Morris (musician)|Trevor Morris]] composed the show's music.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/>\n\nThe show's art style was heavily influenced by the work [[Ayami Kojima]] did for ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]''.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> They also took ideas from director [[Satoshi Kon]]'s works for character expressions and series such as ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]'' and ''[[Berserk: The Golden Age Arc|Berserk]]'' for inserting humor among the more serious elements.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/> The show is produced using 2D [[hand-drawn animation]], taking cues from ''[[Ninja Scroll]]'' and ''[[Vampire Hunter D#Adaptations|Vampire Hunter D]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2017/07/19/interview-adi-shankar-discusses-castlevania-and-assassin-s-creed/|title=Interview: Adi Shankar Discusses Castlevania And Assassin's Creed|website=WWG}}</ref> with staff members that previously worked on ''[[Vampire Hunter D: Bloodlust]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2017/05/25/new-netflix-castlevania-animated-series-goes-full-on-vampire-hunter-d-and-looks-suitably-great/|title=New Netflix 'Castlevania' Animated Series Goes Full On 'Vampire Hunter D' And Looks Suitably Great|first=Ollie|last=Barder|publisher=}}</ref> The [[manga]] series ''[[Berserk (manga)|Berserk]]'' and ''[[Blade of the Immortal]]'' were also cited as inspiration, with one of the show's animation directors having previously worked on the [[Berserk: The Golden Age Arc|''Berserk'' films]].<ref name=\"io9\">{{cite news |last=Narcisse |first=Evan |title=The Animation Studio That Made Castlevania Explains Why It Was a Dream Project |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/the-animation-studio-that-made-castlevania-explains-why-1797476526 |work=[[io9]] |agency=[[Gizmodo]] |date=August 2, 2017}}</ref> The production works closely with [[Konami]], the holders of the ''Castlevania'' franchise, who helped to identify small continuity issues but were otherwise very receptive towards the work.<ref name=\"dtoid\"/>\n\nThe first season of four 30-minute episodes was released on July 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jacob|title=Netflix Quietly Announces Castlevania Series For 2017|url=http://www.cbr.com/netflix-quietly-announces-castlevania-series-for-2017|website=CBR.com|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> This season represents the first part of the trilogy that Ellis has laid out in 2007.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> The second season is eight episodes long and was released on October 26, 2018.<ref name=\"deadlines2\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/castlevania-animated-series-renewed-season-2-netflix-1202125024/| title='Castlevania' Animated Series Renewed For Season 2 By Netflix| first=Denise| last=Petski| date=July 7, 2017| website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/netflix-announces-castlevania-animated-series |title=Netflix Announces Animated Castlevania Series |first=Jonathan |last=Dornbrush |date=February 8, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209003832/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/02/08/netflix-announces-castlevania-animated-series |archivedate=February 9, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-the-first-trailer-for-netflixs-castlevania-s/1100-6450314/ |title=Watch The First Trailer For Netflix's Castlevania Show; Release Date Announced |first=Chris |last=Pereira |date=May 24, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017 |website=[[GameSpot]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626174614/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-the-first-trailer-for-netflixs-castlevania-s/1100-6450314/ |archivedate=June 26, 2017 }}</ref> Ellis said that the second season, completing the trilogy, is where he had been able to deviate somewhat from the game, and has been better anticipate the show's release on Netflix in terms of scenes and episode lengths.<ref name=\"paste magazine\"/> Shankar believes that there is an opportunity for more stories to be told borrowing from other games in the series, noting that overall he sees the series as \"a story about a family and multiple generations of this family\" with many tales to draw from.<ref name=\"polygon july11\"/> The production team for the second season included staff members who worked on [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]] productions such as ''[[Death Parade]]''.<ref name=\"io9\"/>\n\nDeveloping the character of Dracula, [[Adi Shankar]] made it clear that one of the series' main goals has been to paint Dracula not as a villain, but a tragic, doomed figure. According to him: \"The best villains, in general, are the heroes of their own story and the trick to making ''Castlevania'' resonate was this idea that Dracula isn't a bad guy, he isn't a villain, he's just a person consumed with darkness. That first episode in Season 1 we start to see why he wants to eradicate humans. He's not just this mustache-curling, one-dimensional villain. What Dracula is doing is not really a war against humanity. It's more a suicide note.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/10/27/castlevania-season-2-showrunner-on-why-dracula-is-consumed-with-darkness | title = Castlevania Season 2: Showrunner on Why Dracula Is 'Consumed With Darkness' | first = Jesse | last = Schedeen | date = October 27, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\nThe show's third season was greenlit by Netflix a few days after the broadcast of the second season.<ref name=\"s3 greenlit\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/10/castlevania-renewed-season-3-netflix-richard-armitage-james-callis-1202493302/ | title = \u2018Castlevania\u2019 Renewed For Season 3 On Netflix | first=  Erik | last = Pederson | date = October 31, 2018 | accessdate = October 31, 2018 | work = [[Deadline Hollywood]] }}</ref> Shankar announced in November 2018 that he will also be leading an animated series based on Capcom's ''[[Devil May Cry]]'', which he acquired the rights for himself, and will make the show, alongside the ''Castlevania'' series, part of a shared \"[[Bootleg Multiverse]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/16/devil-may-cry-series-joins-castlevania-in-new-multiverse-from-adi-shankar | title = Devil May Cry Series Joins Castlevania In New Multiverse From Adi Shankar | first = David | last = Griffin | date = November 16, 2018 | accessdate = November 16, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> The third season was released on March 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Elfring |first=Matt |title=Here's What's New to Netflix in March 2020: Castlevania Season 3, More Movies, TV Shows, and Originals |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/heres-whats-new-to-netflix-in-march-2020-castlevan/1100-6473892/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=6 March 2020 |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Audience viewership===\nAccording to Parrot Analytics, ''Castlevania'' was the most popular digital original series in the [[United States]] during July 6{{ndash}}19, 2017, with the show generating 23,175,616 \"demand expressions\" on average.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anime-style Netflix series 'Castlevania' proved to be a hit with audiences|url=http://foundremote.com/anime-style-netflixs-series-castlevania-proved-to-be-a-hit-with-audiences/|website=Found Remote|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> According to Parrot Analytics, \"demand expressions\" indicate the \"total audience demand being expressed for a title, within a country,\"<ref name=\"parrotanalytics\">{{cite web|title=The Global Television Demand Report|url=https://insights.parrotanalytics.com/hubfs/Resources/whitepapers/Parrot%20Analytics%20-%20The%20Global%20TV%20Demand%20Report%202017.pdf|website=Parrot Analytics|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> measured by video streams and downloads as well as social media.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Netflix's 'Ozark' Was Most Popular Streaming Show This Summer, According to New Audience Metric|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/netflix-ratings-nielsen-defenders-full-house-house-of-cards-1201888675/|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt remained the 7th most in-demand digital original show in the United States through October 11, 2017.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> By the end of 2017, ''Castlevania'' was the year's 15th most in-demand digital original series in the United States, averaging 18,137,196 demand expressions throughout the year. It was also one of the year's top{{nbsp}}20 most in-demand digital original series in the [[United Kingdom]] (20th), [[Japan]] (4th), [[Brazil]] (10th), [[Mexico]] (11th), [[France]] (13th), [[Canada]] (14th), [[Germany]] (19th) and [[Australia]] (20th).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Global Television Demand Report|url=https://insights.parrotanalytics.com/hubfs/Resources/whitepapers/Parrot%20Analytics%20-%20The%20Global%20TV%20Demand%20Report%202017.pdf|website=Parrot Analytics|year=2017|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy the time the second season became available in 2018, ''Castlevania'' had reportedly garnered nearly 30{{nbsp}}million viewers worldwide according to Netflix analytics, becoming one of the most successful original animated shows on Netflix.<ref>{{cite news |title=30 Years Later: From Nintendo to Netflix, \u2018Castlevania III: Dracula\u2019s Curse\u2019 Unfolds a New Legacy |url=https://goombastomp.com/30-years-later-from-nintendo-to-netflix-castlevania-iii-draculas-curse-unfolds-a-new-legacy/comment-page-1/ |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=Goomba Stomp |date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 80% of critics have given the first season a positive review based on 25 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 7.39/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"''Castlevania'' offers spectacular visuals and a compelling adaptation in its all-too-short first season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/castlevania/s01 |title=Castlevania: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref> It is the first video game adaptation in the site's history to receive a \"Fresh\" rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/netflix-castlevania-broke-rotten-tomatoes-record/ |title= Netflix animated series just lifted a curse: It's the first video game adaptation to get a Fresh rating |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which assigns a rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, reported that there were \"generally favorable reviews\" for the first season, with an weighted average score of 71 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/castlevania |title=Castlevania - TV Show Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Verge]]'' gave a mixed review, noting that the gore did little to create a sense of danger and felt \"intentionally flashy\". It concluded that \"''Castlevania'' is ripe with potential, but also burdened with cliches.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15938192/netflix-castlevania-review-animated-video-game-adaptation |title=Netflix's Castlevania isn't a perfect video game adaptation, but it's on the right track |first=Michael |last=Moore |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=[[The Verge]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062348/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/7/15938192/netflix-castlevania-review-animated-video-game-adaptation |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> Dave Trumbore of [[Collider (website)|Collider]] gave the series four stars out of five, praising the chemistry between the cast and comparing the violence with anime such as ''[[Ninja Scroll]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/castlevania-review-netflix/ |title='Castlevania' Review: Netflix's Video Game Adaptation Has Some Serious Bite |first=Dave |last=Trumbore |date=July 8, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=Collider |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708165546/http://collider.com/castlevania-review-netflix/ |archivedate=July 8, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[IGN]]'' also wrote glowingly of Warren Ellis's script, but felt some of his humor was a little jarring.<ref name=\"IGNReview\"/> In a review for ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]'', Dave Raposo wrote that ''Castlevania'' channeled the cutaway gag formula that is seen in ''[[Family Guy]]''. He dismissed the \"absurd\" attempts at humanizing Dracula and called it a \"milquetoast imitation of ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\", noting that the ambitions of the script \"fly in the face of the simple ideals that unify the best entries in the ''Castlevania'' series\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/08/netflixs-castlevania-series-forgets-what-makes-the.html |title=Netflix's Castlevania Series Forgets What Makes the Games Work |first=Dave |last=Raposo |date=September 7, 2017 |accessdate=September 7, 2017 |website=Paste Magazine}}</ref> Several reviews lauded the voice cast, particularly Graham McTavish as Dracula and Richard Armitage as Trevor Belmont.<ref name=\"IGNReview\">{{cite web |url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/07/09/castlevania-season-1-review |title=CASTLEVANIA: SEASON 1 REVIEW |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen |date=July 8, 2017 |accessdate=July 8, 2017 |website=[[IGN]]}}</ref> ''[[Screen Rant]]''{{'s}} Sarah Moran drew attention to the \"sarcastic edge\" that Armitage brought to the character, and also noted Callis's \"air of sophistication\" as Alucard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/castlevania-netflix-season-1-review/ |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 1: Every Episode Reviewed |first=Sarah |last=Moran |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=Screen Rant |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062409/http://screenrant.com/castlevania-netflix-season-1-review/ |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> ''[[Destructoid]]'' also wrote positively of Trevor Belmont as a protagonist, but criticized the animation and added that the character designs were \"flat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-castlevania-season-1--445745.phtml |title=Review: Castlevania (Season 1) |first=Nick |last=Valdez |date=July 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 7, 2017 |website=[[Destructoid]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709050453/https://www.destructoid.com/review-castlevania-season-1--445745.phtml |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref> Dan Seitz at [[Uproxx]] left a negative review, writing that it tried too hard to find profundity in the story of the ''Castlevania'' series. He also cited issues with the pacing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/hitfix/castlevania-netflix/ |title=Netflix's 'Castlevania' Tries Too Hard To Make A Silly Game Profound |first=Dan |last=Seitz |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |website=Uproxx |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709062404/http://uproxx.com/hitfix/castlevania-netflix/ |archivedate=July 9, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nRotten Tomatoes reported that 100% of critics have given the second season a positive review with an average rating of 9.73/10, based on 12 reviews. The critics consensus reads, \"''Castlevania'' sinks its fangs into vampiric lore during a devilishly fun second season that benefits from an expanded sense of scale and episode tally that allows the series to fully spread its leathery wings.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/castlevania/s02 |title=Castlevania: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nComplaints were made towards the pacing and the screen time spent on Dracula's court in season two. Writing for ''[[GameSpot]]'', Michael Rougeau was disappointed that Trevor's group spent the majority of their time in a library, and also said Dracula \"does literally nothing in all the episodes we've seen so far. There's one medium length flashback in which he massacres a council of merchants who offended him, but it's not like that moves the story along\". Rougeau concluded that the action was creatively executed, but he felt that the new cast was given more development and that the previous characters were left to \"tread water\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/netflixs-castlevania-season-2-full-review-dark-met/1100-6462640 |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 2 Full Review: Dark Metamorphosis |first=Michael |last=Rougeau |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=GameSpot}}</ref> [[Film School Rejects]] echoed similar sentiments, who said the second season was more of a complement to the first one. McTavish and the rest of the voice cast were once again met with high praise.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/castlevania-season-2-review/ |title='Castlevania' Season 2 Review: Blood, Guts, and Backstory |first=Meg |last=Shields |date=October 20, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=Film School Rejects}}</ref> In Collider's review for the second series, Dave Trumbore mentioned there \"isn't a weak link in the cast here\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/castlevania-season-2-review/ |title='Castlevania' Season 2 Review: Bigger, Bloodier, and with More Bite Than Ever |first=Dave |last=Trumbore |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=Collider}}</ref> ''[[WhatCulture]]'' wrote very positively of the voice work and also noted the new performances, including Jaime Murray as Carmilla and Adetokumboh M'Cormack as Isaac.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/tv/castlevania-season-2-review-7-ups-and-2-downs?page=4 |title=Castlevania Season 2 Review: 7 Ups And 2 Downs |first=Motzie |last=Dapul |date=October 30, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=WhatCulture}}</ref> ''IGN'' gave the second season a 9.2/10, praising Ellis's approach to ''Castlevania'' as \"witty and self-aware enough to poke fun at itself when necessary\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2018/10/26/netflixs-castlevania-season-2-review |title=Netflix's Castlevania Season 2 Review |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |website=IGN}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bootleg Multiverse]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/80095241''Castlevania''] on [[Netflix]]\n* {{IMDB title|tt6517102}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Castlevania series}}\n{{Frederator Studios}}\n{{Powerhouse Animation Studios}}\n{{Adaptations of Dracula}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American adult animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American supernatural television series]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American adult animated action television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated drama television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated horror television series]]\n[[Category:Animated series based on video games]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animated television series]]\n[[Category:Castlevania]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:Dracula television programmes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Warren Ellis]]\n[[Category:Frederator Studios]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in fiction]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 15th century]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Europe]]\n[[Category:Vampires in animated television]]\n[[Category:Viz Media anime]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in television]]\n[[Category:Works based on Konami video games]]\n", "name_user": "Deemspurer", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castlevania_(TV_series)"}
